<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=/cgi-bin/mrate.pl name=f101948709429458>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=101948709429458>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=101948709429458>The Mote in Solusek's Eye, Part II</a> <a id=fs8 href=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=101948709429458#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Mon, Apr 22nd 10:57 AM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=93845><span id=Sage>Arjaizen</span></a><br><b><span id=Sage>Sage</span></b><br><span id=notbold>197 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [5.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Chapter 2 <br><br>The air stank of sulfur. As bad as it was, Bristal chuckled to herself as she led the last members of the pack into the tunnel. &quot;Zorntok must be going insane,&quot; she snickered under her breath. &quot;With his sense of smell, this is probably killing him. Serves him right for picking on us earlier.&quot; <br><br>She found a stairway leading down, with a lava river flowing beneath it. Though there was blood on the stairs, there were no bodies. &quot;What do you think Arj?&quot; she asked the Erudite. <br><br>&quot;Hmmm... Most likely, the pack has slain all the goblins guarding the entrance,&quot; the wizard replied logically. &quot;If they had failed, the survivors would still be here, no doubt with reinforcements on the way. Were there only one survivor, he would not have taken the time to dispose of our compatriot's bodies. Rather, he would have immediately gone to get help.&quot; <br><br>Arjaizen looked about the tunnel. &quot;Go down the stairway and to the left. We should see the others shortly.&quot; <br><br>The paladin walked down the stairway with Arjaizen right behind and Alerivers taking up rearguard. Within moments, they reached a window of sorts: a small opening in the wall through which could be seen a small room. In the room, were two goblin corpses. <br><br>&quot;Go ahead through, Bristal,&quot; Arjaizen advised. &quot;You're the only one of us that can fit. The stairs curve around and come back to the room anyway. We will meet you inside.&quot; <br><br>With a nod, the Dwarf ducked and slipped through the opening as Alerivers and the Wizard made their way around, this time with the ranger leading the way. When Alerivers turned a corner, Arjaizen called out, &quot;Watch out for the...&quot; <br><br>Alerivers felt a sudden breeze behind him. He quickly turned, in time to see a jagged piece of his cloak fluttering to the ground, and a huge silvery blade disappearing into a crevice in the wall. <br><br>&quot;...pendulum axe,&quot; Arjaizen finished. &quot;Oh my,&quot; he said as he saw the shredded cloak piece on the floor. Looking up, he took in the ranger's steely glare. &quot;Sorry.&quot; <br><br>His eyes narrowing, Alerivers turned on his heel and stalked off in silence, the Erudite sheepishly following behind. <br><br>--- <br><br>Bending over the corpse of Apalonia, Ainer looked up at Annanicole. &quot;Get Ahmai... and hurry,&quot; he said gravely. The shamaness ran back to where she knew the rest of the pack was regrouping. <br><br>The ambush had trapped them in a dead end room. Eight goblin warriors overwhelmed them, and as Ainer and Annanicole tried to cut them down, Apalonia kept her guildmates healed. By sheer force of numbers, two of the goblins managed to push their way past Ainer, and laid into the young cleric while she was in mid-heal. Though the Wolves were then able to trap the goblins in the room and finish them off, it was too late to save Apalonia, who fell to the blades and claws of the monsters. <br><br>Annanicole returned with Ahmai. Ainer looked up at the Elven priestess and mourned, &quot;There were too many of them... I couldn't reach her in time.&quot; <br><br>Ahmai nodded and laid her hand on Ainer's shoulder. &quot;Don't worry, my friend,&quot; she comforted the distraught Dwarf. &quot;Even now, the healing touch of the Mother of All can reach her.&quot; Chanting in an ancient and almost musical tongue, the cleric cast her spell over her fallen sister of Tunare. Glowing blue strands of mana wove themselves about the corpse, and were gradually absorbed by the body. When the glow had faded, Apalonia's eyes fluttered and opened. She tried to speak, but couldn't find the strength. &quot;Rest, sister,&quot; Ahmai whispered. &quot;Your fight today is done.&quot; <br><br>Turning to Ainer, she said, &quot;She will be to weak to fight for some time. It's too dangerous for her to stay here. You must take her to safety. You're the strongest of us, my friend. She'll need your protection. Annanicole can join you to give you speed and healing if you need it.&quot; She thought for a moment and turned to Annanicole. &quot;Get Boebi. She can guide you back to Freeport.&quot; <br><br>Ainer looked distressed. He didn't want to desert Bristal in her search, for to leave a fellow Dwarf in the hands of the goblins was unthinkable. Ahmai read the pain in his face. &quot;Don't worry, we will not let Crystal stay here. We WILL get her out... even if we have to bring down the mountain to free her.&quot; <br><br>The warrior nodded and gave Ahmai the slightest of smiles. &quot;Yes,&quot; he said gruffly. &quot;Well, see that you do.&quot; <br><br>&quot;We will. Even now, Goldiggin is scouting out every cave and warren. He will find her, and when he does, we'll get her out. I promise.&quot; <br><br>When Annanicole returned with the ranger Boebi, the shamaness of Halas gathered up the Elven cleric in her strong arms, and Ainer led the four up and out of the dungeon. <br><br>After watching them leave, Ahmai turned to rejoin the rest of the pack. &quot;Making the promise is easy, Ahmai,&quot; she said to herself. &quot;But how will only six Wolves keep it?&quot; <br><br>--- <br><br>Goldiggin scouted the way down, luring what guards he found back to the pack. Between his and Aleriver's snares and the root spells of Ahmai, Bristal, and Arjaizen, none escaped to give word of the invading party's presence. Past lava streams and through secret passages, the Fallen Wolves made their way further down into the mountain. Soon, they emerged into a room guarded by what appeared to be a miniature red dragon. It turned toward them as they entered and hissed at them angrily. <br><br>&quot;Oh look, how cute,&quot; Bristal said sweetly. &quot;I wonder what it tastes like?&quot; <br><br>The creature dove at the paladin in attack, and exhaled a plume of flame, singeing Bristal's beard. In response, the Dwarf smashed it with her shield, and clipped its tail with her sword. as it regained its composure in mid-flight, every caster in the pack hit it with a damaging spell, and Bristal slashed it with her blade. It quickly fell to the ground in a smoking heap. Bristal tore off a charred piece of flesh and popped it into her mouth. &quot;Mmmmm... not bad. Almost, but not quite, entirely unlike chicken.&quot; <br><br>Looking a bit queasy at her friend's dietary selection, Ahmai told the group, &quot;Okay, this looks as defenseable a spot as any. We'll pull from here. Let's get started.&quot; <br><br>--- <br><br>Seeing the last of his cousins fall, The goblin warrior decided discretion was the only part of valor and fled the room, slamming the door behind it. <br><br>&quot;I couldn't get a snare on him,&quot; Alerivers called out. <br><br>&quot;He resisted my root,&quot; added Ahmai. &quot;Arj?&quot; <br><br>The wizard shook his head in frustration, &quot;No mana.&quot; <br><br>Goldiggin ran towards the door, saying, &quot;I'll get him...&quot; <br><br>The body of the goblin burst through the door, showering splinters throughout the room. It crashed to the floor in a broken, crumbled heap. <br><br>&quot;...or not,&quot; Goldiggin finished, stopping abruptly. <br><br>Through the demolished doorway stepped a half-sized Crushor Smashgud. &quot;Nok, nok! Lo' Wolves!&quot; he said with a jagged-toothed grin. <br><br>Looking him up and down (mostly down,) Alerivers asked, &quot;Crushor, what happened to you?&quot; <br><br>&quot;Niki shrinked Crushor outside so me can fit in tunnels,&quot; came the reply. &quot;Now Crushor is littler than Ahmai!&quot; <br><br>Goldiggin turned to Zorntok. &quot;Who's Niki?&quot; <br><br>&quot;Annanicole,&quot; the Iksar answered, &quot;He hasss trouble with long namesss.&quot; <br><br>Ahmai hugged the ogre tightly. &quot;Thanks for coming, we really need you.&quot; <br><br>&quot;Enough huggy, touchy, and feely,&quot; Zorntok complained. &quot;We do more killing of goblinsssss and lessss mouthsss never stopping? So we can get out of ssstinking dungeon?&quot; <br><br>&quot;What's the matter LEE-zard,&quot; Bristal teased, &quot;You don't like it here?&quot; <br><br>The Iksar snorted and shook his head. &quot;No, the sssmell isss maddening!&quot; <br><br>The cleric rolled her eyes, and agreed. &quot;All right, Zorntok. Goldiggin, you check that tunnel, see if you can find Crystal. Try not to be seen. Alerivers, you try the other tunnel. If something spots you, bring it here, ok? <br><br>With two nods of their heads, the druid and the ranger went their separate ways while the rest of the pack rested and meditated. <br><br>--- <br><br>In his forest domain, a ranger can camouflage himself so deftly that a person could stand not 5 feet away from him and still not know he was there. One as skilled as Alerivers could pick an apple off the head of an orc at 200 yards with his bow...though he'd rather pick off the head OF the orc. Yet in this steaming dungeon, Alerivers felt nothing but frustration. It would be hard to imagine a place where he felt more out of his element. Yet here is where he was needed, so here he was. With no natural covering, he did the best he could to &quot;hide in plain sight.&quot; Time and again, he lured one, two, or three goblins to their deaths at the hands of the wolf pack. <br><br>He had come to the end of open corridors, and was now faced with a door. He had no idea what lay beyond, but he couldn't delay taking chances any longer. He reached for the door latch... <br><br>The handle flew from his grasp as the door was opened from within. Pulled off-balance, the ranger fell a step forward into the room, and faced four angry goblins. &quot;An intruder!&quot; their leader yelled, as Alerivers turned to run back to the pack. &quot;After it!&quot; <br><br>As the ranger ran down the corridor, the leader stepped into the hallway and began an arcane chant. Suddenly, Alerivers staggered forward as flames exploded all about him. He thanked the gods for the spells protecting him from the brunt of the blast. He ran on, leading the pursuing train of goblins to the rest of the Fallen Wolves. He burst into the room, calling out, &quot;Incoming! Four of them, at least one caster!&quot; <br><br>The first of the pursuers ran headlong into the sword of Crushor. Though half his normal size, his strength was undiminished, and the goblin was fortunate to deflect the blade. The goblin wizard saw the power of Crushor's attack and immediately unleashed a spell causing flame to wash all over the ogre. <br><br>Seeing the wizard cast his spell, and its effect, Arjaizen began to cast a spell of his own. As the goblin prepared to hurl another flaming blast at Crushor, he was hammered by a wall of force that threw him back ten feet, crushing his ribcage and leaving him stunned. While he tried to gather his wits, the Erudite cast again, and a column of pure mana exploded all about the goblin, and his flesh blistered and burned. As he pulled himself back to his feet to attempt a counterspell, Alerivers burst through the line of attack and with four blindingly swift slashes of his blades, cut the wizard down for good. <br><br>Without the magical support of the wizard, the rest of the goblin warriors quickly fell victim to the pack. Looking over the corpse of the goblin wizard, Alerivers came across a strange artifact. &quot;Arjaizen,&quot; he called, &quot;do you recognize this item?&quot; <br><br>The Erudite gasped in amazement as he took the item, that bore a striking resemblance to a glowing heart. &quot;The Heart of Fire,&quot; he whispered. &quot;This is an item I have heard the legend of, but never truly believed was real. If the rest of the legend is true...&quot; He looked up at the rest of the pack. &quot;Friends, in the Temple of Solusek Ro there is a tome that tells of the Staff of Temperate Flux. According to the legend, the Staff grants the wizard that wields it the power to give his elemental spells more power against his enemies. To acquire the staff, the wizard must return four items to the Temple: The Staff of Ro, a Rod of Bone, the Heart of Frost... and the Heart of Fire.&quot; <br><br>&quot;Then keep thisss heart, wizard,&quot; Zorntok stated. &quot;Your power is oursss. We are a pack.&quot; <br><br>&quot;Aye,&quot; said Bristal. &quot;If the legend is true, we'll help you complete this quest. But for now, we need rest. And hope.&quot; <br><br>As they rested, regaining their strength and mana, Goldiggin returned. &quot;I found her,&quot; he said breathlessly. &quot;We need to hurry.&quot; <br><br>&quot;All right,&quot; Bristal said. &quot;If we're going to get out, we'll need to come through here. Crushor, Alerivers, and Zorntok, you stay and hold this position. Ahmai, Arj, you come with me. May Brell be with us. Lead on, Gold.&quot; <br><br>--- <br><br><br>&quot;It's around here, through a small opening in the wall.&quot; Goldiggin whispered as they rounded a bend. &quot;There's a lava river, and Crystal's hanging over it.&quot; <br><br>The opening was well-hidden. Indeed, Arjaizen had been past it several times before and not noticed it. While they walked through the small passage, he checked his map again. &quot;This isn't on the map, Goldiggin.&quot; <br><br>&quot;I know,&quot; the druid answered. &quot;I only found it when I noticed some tracks going where they shouldn't.&quot; As they stepped out into a large chamber, he added, &quot;We're here.&quot; <br><br>As his compatriots entered the chamber, Arjaizen cast an invisibility spell upon himself before following them in. Bristal entered just before him, and saw a large stream of lava flowing through the chamber. A small bridge crossed the stream at the other end of the chamber, and a curling stairway led up to a high platform. On a support column of the platform was a large iron ring, through which there was a tied-off rope. This rope threaded upwards to the ceiling of the chamber, and through another ring in the ceiling. Hanging down from ceiling, the other end of the rope was tied firmly about the wrists of a dangling Dwarven female, gently swinging above the lava stream. <br><br>&quot;CRYSTAL!&quot; Bristal shouted up at his sister. &quot;We're here! We'll get you down.&quot; <br><br>Hearing her sister calling her name, the young rogue looked around the floor of the chamber wearily. &quot;Bris?&quot; She called out weakly. &quot;S' a trap... get away, go...away.&quot; <br><br>&quot;Not without you,&quot; the paladin called back to her sister. &quot;Arj.... Arj?&quot; She turned to look at Goldiggin, anger flashing in her eyes. &quot;Where is he?&quot; <br><br>Up on the platform, a figure in pale blue skin appeared next to the rope. In a loud voice, it called down to them. &quot;Gax'r Dwarfbane is my name, in Butcherblock, my kin were slain. Killed by these dwarves, with axe and knife, now YOU shall pay, with pain, and life.&quot; Breaking from his rhymes, the goblin raised a fine steel sword high as he called down to Bristal. &quot;You want your sister? Well, you can have her...well done!&quot; <br><br>Out of the corner of his eye, Goldiggin caught a swirl of mists where there should have been none. Ahmai said to him, &quot;I thought you said he'd be here when we needed him!&quot; <br><br>In Elvish, the Feir'Dal druid answered her softly, &quot;Have faith... and be ready for anything.&quot; <br><br>Gax'r slashed down hard with the sword, slicing through the rope as though it were a stalk of wheat. As the swordblade fell, a flash of red and white light appeared on the other end of the platform, and Arjaizen appeared in it's center, casting a spell which he targeted at Crystal. As she fell, his spell slammed into her with a mighty force, and she screamed in pain as she was struck. The impact had another effect though, and that was to hurl her further away from the wizard, and rather than landing in the lava river, she fell heavily at it's bank. <br><br>Bristal and Ahmai ran to her side. Crystal looked up at her sister, blood dripping from her mouth. Her eyelids fluttered, and she whispered, &quot;Thanks, for trying...&quot; As her eyes started to roll back, Ahmai called on the healing power of Tunare, and life came back into the rogue as much, though not all, of her injuries were healed. <br><br>Gax'r turned towards Arjaizen and charged the Erudite with sword held high. The wizard waved his arm through the air before the goblin, and Gax'r stopped in his tracks. As Arjaizen advanced upon the goblin, he said in verse, &quot;You sought your vengeance in Solusek's Eye, but now, little goblin... it's time... to die.&quot; <br><br>The others on the cavern floor heard the blast of the spell and looked up in time to see Gax'r fly over the edge of the platform, then plunge into the center of the lava river, disappearing in a burst of steam. Then, walking on air, Arjaizen stepped over the ledge and slowly drifted down towards them, glowing particles trailing from his fingertips. &quot;Is your sister all right, Bristal?&quot; <br><br>&quot;She'll be okay,&quot; the paladin answered. &quot;We'll heal her up the rest of the way and...&quot; <br><br>&quot;Wait,&quot; the Erudite answered. &quot;We are leaving, and those healing spells may be later needed to save a life. Can you walk, Crystal?&quot; <br><br>Nodding, Crystal answered, &quot;I can walk. My leg's a bit messed up still, but I can make it.&quot; <br><br>&quot;Good,&quot; Arjaizen replied. &quot;Goldiggin, take us to the others... and as quickly as you can manage.&quot; <br><br>--- <br><br>They returned to their pull-point in the middle of chaos. Four warriors and two shamen were battering the Wolves that had stayed to hold the escape route open. Though the group tried to focus on one opponent at a time, the goblins were swarming upon them too quickly, and the pack's tactics rapidly disintegrated. Ahmai cast heals upon Alerivers and Crushor, and immediately attracted the attention of two warriors. Goldiggin came to her aid, and was attacked by two warriors, upon one of whom Arjaizen unleashed a Force Shock spell. Four more goblins of varying types came through another doorway, and the group found themselves surrounded. <br><br>Seeing the group being decimated, with more reinforcements likely on the way, Ahmai shouted in Elvish for Goldiggin to evacuate the group with a teleportation spell. Arjaizen blasted Goldiggin's remaining attacker, stunning him momentarily as the badly wounded druid began to cast his spell of evacuation. When the goblin recovered, he turned his attentions upon the wizard, who with all the casting he had already done, was defenseless against the goblin's longsword. <br><br>A few quick slashes of that sword, and Arjaizen found himself back against a wall, with the goblin closing in on the kill, and the world seemingly moving in slow motion before his eyes... <br><br>...Crystal had picked up a dagger from the lifeless hand of a fallen goblin. She turned and saw her sister valiantly defending Goldiggin as the druid desperately tried to complete his evac spell. Just as he finished the last word of the spell, and the portal began to form, one goblin broke past the Dwarven paladin and stabbed Goldiggin in the chest... <br><br>...Bristal turned and saw the sword pulled from her packmate's chest and reached out to him, her hand bathed in a soft blue glow... <br><br>...Another goblin noticed the paladin turned away from him and reared back to plunge his sword into her back... <br><br>...even as he began to fall unconscious to the ground and the portal began to collapse, Goldiggin felt the healing touch of Bristal's hand and a warmth suffused his entire body as his wounds disappeared in a heartbeat... <br><br>...Crystal slid her dagger between the ribs of the goblin that had turned on Bristal. The dagger neatly sliced its heart in two, and the goblin dropped its sword as life left its eyes... <br><br>...Goldiggin somehow managed to regain his focus and concentration. Call it luck, single-minded determination, or the combined blessings of Brell and Tunare, but the impossible began to happen: The once-collapsing portal began to reform, and the pack disappeared from the midst of the goblin horde. <br><br>--- <br><br>Goldiggin's spell plucked them from the depths of Solusek's Eye and deposited them in the tunnel leading to the dungeon's entrance. Unfortunately, they found themselves surrounded by another swarm of goblins. As they attacked the Wolves, their commander taunted, &quot;No escape, for the dwarfling's friends! Your suffering here will never end! Your deaths they will be long and slow... you'll beg from this life to go.&quot; <br><br>The battle joined again, the Wolves outnumbered two to one. Crushor unleashed a bellowing battle cry. The spell that shrank him dispelled by the evac, his massive frame blocked the tunnel heading down as his guildmates tried desperately to fight their way back to the surface. <br><br>By sheer happenstance, Arjaizen appeared behind the goblins nearest the entrance, Crystal at his feet. Seeing her sister, Bristal yelled out to the wizard, &quot;Get her out!&quot; Her warning caught the attention of one goblin, who turned to attack the retreating Erudite. <br><br>Goldiggin, re-energized from Bristal's healing touch, tore into the goblin with fury, hacking at it viciously. The goblin turned to face his attacker, all thought of the wounded wizard and crippled Dwarf banished from his mind. <br><br>Zorntok hissed angrily as a goblin's sword bit into his side. Blue light flashed around his warder in response, and engulfed his master's attacker, slashing the goblin with shards of blinding ice. A goblin wizard blasted the warder with a powerful spell, and it fell to ground, seemingly dissolving in a cloud of sparks. The Iksar leaped across the tunnel, landing on the wizard and rending it in blind rage, even as the goblin warrior slashed at the beastlord with its sword. Unable to focus its concentration or even regain its footing, the wizard's death was quick and violent. As the last spark of life winked out of its eyes, Zorntok, his own blood running as though a river, turned to the warrior, and hissed at it once more... <br><br>In the midst of the maelstrom, Ahmai desperately tried to keep her fellow Wolves healed, though she could see she was losing ground. She gave her two last heals to Crushor, who was valiantly keeping another half-dozen goblins at bay. Another warrior, taking note of her healing of the group, stabbed her in the back. Hearing her cry out, Alerivers immediately turned his attention to her attacker, and with a deft slash of his sword, opened a huge gash in its torso. <br><br>The last of the upper goblins fell from the last of Goldiggin's mana. They turned to Crushor, and through the small gaps left between his body and the tunnel walls, could see that at least four goblin corpses lay at his feet. There were still more gathering behind the ones that were left. <br><br>&quot;GO!&quot; Crushor yelled, &quot;I stop them here! They not get by Crushor!&quot; <br><br>Tears in her eyes, Ahmai called out, &quot;No, my love! I won't leave you here to die!&quot; <br><br>The ogre staggered from the blast of a wizard's spell. As most ogre warriors, Crushor was not blessed with great intelligence, but even he knew his was a losing battle. Still, he could not let Ahmai and his friends die here. If he was going to die anyway, he'd make sure they lived. So, he lied. &quot;Get Wolves out! Crushor not die, Crushor smash! Crushor smash gud!&quot; <br><br>She knew it was a lie, but she knew also that they were all dead if they stayed. Ahmai followed the rest of the Fallen Wolves out of the tunnel, supporting the once again near-dead Goldiggin on one side, and the hobbling Bristal on the other. Once they were all clear of the tunnel, she sat down and closed her tearing eyes, and prayed with all her strength for Tunare to come to her in her time of need. To give her the strength, the power, to do something, anything, to aid the mighty ogre that owned a piece of her heart. <br><br>The Mother of All was also in the forefront of Goldiggin's mind, as the wood elf tried to clear his thoughts, and meditate. He needed to regain enough strength to create a portal for Crushor to get out of the dungeon. Suddenly, he heard Bristal cry out, &quot;Ahmai, NO!&quot; <br><br>He opened his eyes in time to see the High-elven cleric disappear down the dusty tunnel. He got to his feet, and staggered down after her. he didn't know if he had recouped enough mana for his spell, but it would have to do. <br><br>She could barely see through the haze now, but still she went on. Crushor was just ahead. A goblin drove his spear through an opening in his armor, and the ogre dropped to one knee as the weapon was twisted and withdrawn. &quot;NOOOO...,&quot; he cried as a goblin started to claw its way past him. <br><br>Ahmai called on Tunare one more time and cast her most powerful healing spell. Enough of Crushor's strength returned for him to force the goblin back in front of him, and he got to his feet once more. Goldiggin began to cast his portal spell. The gate began to form, but collapsed, as he didn't have quite enough power to get it off. He used what mana he had left to give the ogre what healing he could, then gathered Ahmai up, and led her out of the tunnel again. <br><br>Crushor looked around at the tunnel. All the explosions from the spells had left cracks in the walls. He knew when he fell, the goblins would pull his body out of the way and swarm out to overwhelm his friends. He threw his sword behind himself and reached out to grab hold of the tunnel supports. With all of his strength, and perhaps a little more, he strained against them, and they slowly were torn loose. With the sound of rolling thunder, hundreds of tons of stone and dust began to cascade down as the mountain began to fall around them. <br><br>Goldiggin helped Ahmai sit at the tunnel's end and dropped heavily down next to her. Suddenly, they felt the rumbling of the mountain as a cloud of dust billowed out of the tunnel. Ahmai buried her face in her hands and sobbed. When she heard the druid gasp, she looked up. Up the dust-filled corridor, a towering figure was slowly staggering, one huge hand bracing the wall as the other dragged an enormous sword behind it. <br><br>Blood pouring from countless wounds and pain etched on his face, Crushor inched his way out of the dungeon of Solusek's Eye. It would be a long time before anyone made their way back in, but that didn't concern him. He looked up and saw Ahmai and Goldiggin staring at him. At the sight of them, he straightened himself, and hardened his expression, hiding the pain as best he could. &quot;See Ahmai,&quot; he rasped, &quot;Crushor not... die. Crushor smash... gud.&quot; With that, he slowly sat next to them and closed his eyes. <br><br>--- <br><br>It was raining in the Butcherblock Mountains as Goldiggin appeared in the center of the Druid ring along with his passengers. &quot;You two sure you're going to be okay?&quot; <br><br>&quot;Yeah, we'll be fine, Gold,&quot; Bristal responded. &quot;The gobbies around here are scred to death of us, and I can handle any of the undead we run into. I'll see ya at the guild house in a week or so. Ready Crys?&quot; <br><br>Crystal nodded. &quot;Yeah, let's go. I'd kinda like to get into a nice cave that doesn't stink of sulfur... or gobbies.&quot; She waved to the druid and said, &quot;Seeya Goldiggin. Thanks for the lift... and the help.&quot; <br><br>Goldiggin shrugged. &quot;No problem,&quot; he said. &quot;Wolves take care of their own.&quot; <br><br>With a wave, he began to weave another gating spell, and with a shimmering of bluish white light, faded away. Bristal turned to her sister and said, &quot;C'mon, Crys, let's go home. I've got a couple bottles of ale for you to try. Arjaizen said he made 'em from an old Dwarven receipe, and ya know, they ain't half bad...&quot; <br><br>fini<br><br></p>&nbsp;<br><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>Arjaizen Izrhume<br>40th Circle Wizard of Erudin<br>Fallen Wolves</td></tr>
