</ul></td></tr></table>

<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=/cgi-bin/mrate.pl name=f101846056214319>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=101846056214319>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=101846056214319>The Mote in Solusek's Eye</a> <a id=fs8 href=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=101846056214319#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Wed, Apr 10th 1:47 PM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=93845><span id=Sage>Arjaizen</span></a><br><b><span id=Sage>Sage</span></b><br><span id=notbold>197 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [4.79]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Prologue<br><br>The young dwarf crept through the underbrush with almost unnatural stealth.&nbsp;&nbsp;The sound of combat was just ahead. An almost evil smile came on her face as she came out of the bushes right behind the goblin.  <br><br>She held her dagger firmly at waist height.  An odd thought crossed her mind: Most people's mental image of a back stabbing has the attacker raising their dagger high over their head.  Actually, this is almost never the case.  The far more effective attack involves sliding a thin blade horizontally between the ribs behind the heart.  A perfect stabbing will drop the largest of opponents in seconds, as their lacerated heart spills its vital fluids and stops beating.  Even a more poorly-placed attack can be devastating.  <br><br>She saw her opening and swiftly plunged her dagger into the goblins back.  A bit too hastily, she missed her mark, but the monster was near to death anyway, and the stabbing finished it off.  As the corpse collapsed to the ground, Crystal looked up at... herself.<br><br>Bristal's eyes narrowed as she looked at her twin.  &quot;Do you HAVE to do that?  I could have finished it off myself, you know.&quot;  As an aspiring paladin of Brell, the fact that her sister chose to follow Bristlebane and the way of the rogue was more than a little annoying.  The shame Crystal had brought upon the family was <br>embarassing, but even Bristal had to admit that her sister's skill at dropping an opponent through stealth and guile was improving rapidly.  Better to have the help than not.<br><br>As she bent over the corpse, she asked, &quot;You didn't poison the blade, did you, Crystal?&quot;<br><br>Crystal shook her head. &quot;No, it's too expensive to waste on one of these.  Besides, they die too quick anyway.  Kind of pointless, you know?&quot;<br><br>The paladin smiled, and said, &quot;Good,&quot; as she began to carve a large portion of the goblin's thigh off the bone and placed it carefully in a jar with seasonings. &quot;This'll make a decent stew, I think.  A bit greasy, but all the more filling, eh?&quot;  <br><br>When she was finished, she cleaned off her blade and the two sisters made their way further into the valleys of the Butcherblock Mountain range, oblivious to the the red-tinged eyes watching them through the dense undergrowth a short distance away.  Gax'r clenched his teeth with hatred.  A mere whelp, he knew that to attack them would be suicide... something his older cousin should have thought of.  Then again, neither of them had seen the assassin hiding in the bushes.  <br><br>These two had been killing scores of the Butcherblock horde.  The one with the axe had called the assassin &quot;Crystal.&quot;  He would need to find out who these two were.  The goblin clans often fought among themselves, but were united in their hatred for these hideous dwarves.  Perhaps he was a whelp now, but that would not always be true.  Someday, he'd find a way to get his revenge.<br><br>---------<br><br>Chapter 1<br><br>The noise in the guild hall was amazing, especially considering that only a few short months ago, the Fallen Wolves were thought to be at death's door.  Most of their members had left for other guilds, yet a small core had remained.  With a new leader, the core grew, and even thrived, much as a light-starved plant might thrive if the thicket around it was thinned.  The fact was that the Wolves were as strong as they had ever been, and Bristal couldn't help but feel proud to be a part of it.<br><br>She walked over to the bar and climbed up onto one of the stools.  She called out to the barkeep in a loud voice, &quot;Yo' Pharis, slide a BB Stout over here.&quot;<br><br>Pharis cringed at the order. &quot;Blackburrow Stout?&quot; he asked.  &quot;Do you know what's IN that?&quot;<br><br>The paladin scratched her beard as though in thought, and answered, &quot;Nope.  Don't care what's in it either.  Just care about what it does when it's in me.  So send it down here, or I'll tell you what I'm having for dinner.&quot;<br><br>&quot;BB Stout... coming up,&quot; the bartender answered hesitantly.  Bristal's diet was one of the big topics of guild gossip.  It was said she'd eat anything, given the right combination of sauces and spices, and he didn't want to be the one to find out if it was true.<br><br>As she drank the strong draught, Bristal heard someone call out, &quot;Letter for Bristal!&quot;  She got down off the stool and headed over to the reception desk, where she saw a courier from the League of Antonican Bards.  &quot;I'm Bristal,&quot; she said. &quot;What've you got?&quot;<br><br>&quot;Letter for you Sir...ahh...Miss.  Umm... sorry,&quot; the courier stuttered.<br><br>With a grimace, Bristal snatched the letter from his hand, turned on her heel, and walked back to her bar stool, grumbling.  &quot;'Sir', he said, eh?  Way to blow a tip, kid.&quot;  She climbed back up onto her stool and looked at the letter.  The paper had an odd feel to it, almost like something made brittle and dried out by fire.  The writing was almost a scrawl, legible, but only barely.  She broke the seal and began to read the letter, written in Common.<br><br>   You don't know me, dwarf, but I know you,<br>   on my cousins, you once chewed.<br><br>   I'll have my revenge, your sister is mine,<br>   She waits for you in the fire god's eye.<br><br>There was no signature, but there was no need.  No one new why goblins found such fascination with poetry, but there was no doubt the message was penned by one.  The &quot;fire god's eye&quot; could only be one place:  Solusek's Eye, home of the Fire Goblins.  Somewhere, deep inside a dungeon in the Lavastorm Mountains, the Fire goblins had Crystal prisoner.<br><br>---<br><br>&quot;I've got to go,&quot; she growled.  &quot;She's a pain the butt, but she's still my sister, and I ain't gonna let no stinkin' gobbie eat her!&quot;<br><br>&quot;Of course you have to go, Bris,&quot; Ahmai answered.  The High Elven cleric of Tunare tried to calm her friend, which was something of a part time job for her.  Dwarves were legendary for their incendiary personalities, and Bristal was no exception.  &quot;Of course you have to go... and I'm coming with you.&quot;<br><br>&quot;Nope.  Can't ask you into this,&quot; the paladin answered,  &quot;It's got nothing to do with you.  My family, my job.&quot;<br><br>&quot;You didn't ask me,&quot; Ahmai replied, &quot;and I didn't ask you.  I'm a Wolf, just as you are.  Your family is my family.  And besides, Wolves hunt in packs.&quot;<br><br>Bristal hoisted her pack on her shoulder, and said, &quot;Thanks, Ahmai, but two wolves aren't a pack.&quot;<br><br>As her dwarven friend began to open the door, Ahmai answered, &quot;No, they're not... but six are.&quot;<br><br>When she stepped out the door, Bristal came face to face with four other Wolves:  Boebi the ranger, Zorntok, beastlord of the Iksar, Goldiggin the druid, and Arjaizen, wizard of Erudin.  As she looked at the four of them in surprise, the Erudite asked, &quot;What took you so long? we've been waiting for almost 15 minutes. shall we go?&quot; <br><br>---<br><br>As they prepared to leave, Arjaizen, new to the guild, looked at Bristal critically.  The wizard knew that going into Solusek's Eye was extremely dangerous; he had, after all been there already with Goldiggin before they joined the Fallen Wolves.  He had also heard of Bristal's reputation in battle:  Valiant, steadfast, stubborn, and brave beyond all reason.  If the situation got dire, and it quite likely could, she would need all the protection she could get.  He came to a decision.  &quot;Go on without me,&quot; he said.  &quot;I have other business to attend to.  I will meet you at the entrance to Solusek's Eye in three days time.&quot;  With that, he cast a spell, opening a gate to another part of the world.  It closed about him and he vanished from sight, leaving four of his companions looking at Goldiggin.<br><br>&quot;Does he do this often?&quot;  The ranger Boebi wasn't in the least bit amused.  Goldiggin was Arjaizen's friend, and Boebi stared daggers at the druid as though he was a co-conspirator.<br><br>&quot;Disappear without a second's notice or a word of explanation?  Not more than a couple of times a week,&quot; Goldiggin answered.  &quot;Don't worry,  when we need him, he'll be there.  Hasn't let me down yet.&quot;<br><br>Grumbling, the five made there way to the front door of the guild hall.  At the entrance, they met several other Wolves: The warrior Ainer from Kaladim, Apalonia the cleric, and Annanicole, shamaness of Halas.  Ainer said to Bristal, &quot;Heard about your sister.  We're going too... and I don't want to hear a word otherwise, got me?&quot;<br><br>Bristal cocked her head to one side, thought for a moment, shrugged her shoulder, and said, &quot;Fine.  The more, the merrier, I guess.&quot;  <br><br>Turning to Goldiggin, she asked, &quot;Can you get us any closer than this?&quot;<br><br>The druid nodded his head.  &quot;Sure, I can port us all to the druid ring in West Commons.  From there, we can make our way on foot to Nektulos Forest, then on to the Lavastorm Mountains.  It'll take us three days, but that's a lot better than the alternative.&quot;<br><br>&quot;Okay then, let's go,&quot; said Bristal.  &quot;I want to get going.  The sooner we leave, the sooner Crystal's out of the hands of those gobbies.&quot;<br><br>Goldiggin gathered the Wolves into two groups, and one group at a time, ported them to the West Commons druid ring.  As the second group appeared, they felt the ground start to shake. &quot;What is it, a quake?&quot; <br><br>With eyes as sharp as an eagle, Boebi scanned the horizon, at the same time sensing the the flow of the ground tremors.  Pointing toward the south, the ranger exclaimed, &quot;No!  It's a hill giant! <br>To the south, but coming this way!&quot;<br><br>Ainer drew his weapon. &quot;Then it comes to it's death!&quot;<br><br>Ahmai put her delicate hand on Ainer's shoulder and sad, &quot;No, my friend... not this time.  We have to hurry.&quot;<br><br>&quot;You're right,&quot; the Dwarf agreed.  &quot;We could kill it, but it will take time, and we've little to waste.  We should go, and quickly.&quot;<br><br>With that, Bristal turned to the ranger and said, &quot;Okay, lead us to Nektulos Forest!&quot; Looking to the south, she could just see the enormous head of the hill giant beginning to appear at the creast of a distant hill. &quot;...and now would be a good time!&quot; she added.<br><br>---<br><br>Thanks to spells from Annanicole and Goldiggin, the wolf pack's journey was swift.  The sun was setting as they approached the pass that led to Nektulos Forest, near the home of the T'ier Dal - the Dark Elves of Neriak.<br><br>&quot;Make camp here,&quot; Bristal stated.  &quot;Nektulos is bad enough in the daytime.  'Sides, we could use the rest.&quot; The Fallen_Wolves set up their camp and had their dinner.  The night was unnaturally quiet; not even the buzzing of insects could be heard.  The only sound to hear was their own breathing... or the beating of their hearts.  What sleep they could get was fitful, and morning came too soon.<br><br>As they made their way through the pass towards the Nektulos Forest, the air seemed to get thicker and heavier with each step they took.  Darkness descended again; it seemed as though night was falling, even though the sun had risen barely two hours before.<br><br>Zorntok sniffed the air.  The scent of death was everywhere.  He felt no fear, the Iksar never did, but the smell of the walking dead offended his senses.  He much preferred to control the living.  What was sthe challenge in controlling dead flesh with no will?<br><br>His warder trotted alongside him.  Though it could have chosen to go its own way at any time, it did not.  Its devotion to the beastlord was complete; it would gladly give its life in defense of its master.  Knowing this, Zorntok kept it near.  A lack of fear did not mean a lack of caution. <br><br>Despite being accosted by undead seemingly at every turn, they made good time.  Near noon, they approached a bridge crossing a river.  Several T'ier Dal guards stood the watch.  The way to the Lavastorm Mountains lay ahead.  They would need to cross the bridge to continue on.<br><br>Boebi sheathed her weapons, and readied her bow.  Considering the guards carefully, she picked the target that seemed the toughest.  Might as well get the hard part over first, she mused.  The arrow flew straight and true, it wedged in the guard's breastplate.  Though wounded, it wasn't serious, and with a battle cry to his compatriots, he charged the ranger.<br><br>Had the guard given a thought to looking behind, he may have thought the better of his decision; two of his compatriots were rooted to the ground, courtesy of spells cast by Ahmai and Apalonia, the third seemed to be trudging though knee-deep mud for all the progress he was making.  So, the first guard arrived alone, and was quickly slain by the blades of the Wolf Pack.  The rest of the battle went much the same, keen use of spells allowed the pack to fight a single guard at a time, the last rended to pieces by Zorntok and his warder.  Only minor injuries were received by the party, these were easily cured by the clerics.  With no survivors to summon aid, it would be hours before a change of the guard arrived.  They would be long gone by then.  Still, Boebi and Goldiggin took care to cover their tracks.  Even an adept ranger would have had a hard time following their trail, and there were none of them among the T'ier Dal.<br><br>Aside from the inevitable undead attacks, the rest of their journey to the pass toward Lavastorm was without event.  Once again, they made camp for the night.  In spite of still being at the edge of Nektulos, this night they slept deeply, as exhaustion overtook them.<br><br>---<br><br>&quot;Twenty-four plat, eight gold, take it or leave it,&quot; the dwarf said to the robed Erudite.  Arjaizen huffed in frustration, but paid the dwarf his fee.  <br><br>&quot;You should be happy you have no competition here,&quot; he admonished the vendor.  &quot;At these prices, you'd be bankrupt in a month on Norrath.&quot;<br><br>&quot;You should be happy I sell ta you at all,&quot; came the retort. &quot;You can try yer luck in Shadowhaven if ya like.&quot;<br><br>&quot;Hmph.  I think not.  Take your money, give me my goods.&quot;<br><br>As he left the shop, the wizard thought he spotted a familiar face.  A massive ogre in bronze-tinted armor was by one of the bank stalls, exchanging coin.  &quot;Crushor,&quot; Arjaizen asked, &quot;is that you?&quot;<br><br>The orge looked up at the Erudite and scowled for a second, then recognizing his guildmate, grunted. &quot;Hail wizzie Arj.  Thot you wit Ahmai and Bris.&quot;<br><br>&quot;Ah, yes.  I am... or was,&quot; the wizard answered. &quot;They, along with a few other Wolves, are headed to Solusek's Eye in the Lavastorm Mountains.  It seems Bristal's sister is being held captive there by the fire goblins.  We are attempting a rescue.&quot;<br><br>&quot;Ahmai gonna fight goblins?  Crushor go too,&quot; the ogre stated. &quot;You take me.&quot;<br><br>&quot;I wish I could, my friend,&quot; Arjaizen said sincerely, &quot;but I do not yet know the spell to take others to the Nektulos spires.  You'll need to find someone else that can do it.&quot;<br><br>&quot;Okay, I go,&quot; Crushor answered, and without another word, he turned and left.<br><br>---<br><br>They broke camp before dawn.  The heat of the mountains would drain them of energy quickly, and the altitude would make it hard to catch their breath as the march went on, so they needed all the time they could get.<br><br>The glow of the lava pools in the mountain range lit up the sky like an early dawn to the north of the pack as they made their way up the pass.  Though the air was normally cool this time of year, it was quite warm, and would get much hotter by the time they reached Solusek's Eye.  <br><br>When the pass opened up into the mountain range itself, it was near stifling.  Only Zorntok was unaffected.  If anything, the Iksar was energized by the heat.  &quot;You ssoftskins are too sslow,&quot; he taunted as he bounded up a rock face. &quot;Perhaps you sshould have sslept longer.&quot;<br><br>&quot;Yeah, yeah,&quot; Bristal grumbled under her breath as she wiped the sweat off her brow.  &quot;Talk to me in Halas.  I bet you'll be bouncin' off the walls there.&quot;  The paladin was struggling in the heat, and lagging behind her mates.  When they offered to stop to rest, she waved them on.  &quot;I'll catch up, you go on.  Set up a pull-point.&quot;  And so, the rest of the group went.  Once they were out of sight, she changed her direction, and her pace.  Her energy level higher than it had appeared only moments before, she made good time along her new path.<br><br>---<br><br>There were no battles to fight, save the one against the oppressive environment.  The pack reached the cave entrance to Solusek's Eye and girded themselves for battle.  Ahmai set up the marching order:  Ainer, their most experienced warrior, would take the lead until they established their pull-point.  Goldiggin, who would be their scout once inside, would be rear guard.  <br><br>When only Goldiggin was left outside, the air outside the cave began to sparkle with white light.  In the center of it, a familiar red-robed figure appeared, a large bag at its feet.  When the light dispersed, Arjaizen turned to the druid and asked, &quot;Where is Bristal?&quot;<br><br>&quot;Hi Arj, nice to see you too,&quot; the Wood Elf chided.<br><br>The wizard grimaced, then chuckled at himself. &quot;Sorry, my friend. It -is- good to see you well.  I trust the journey here was uneventful?&quot;<br><br>&quot;Not quite, but nothing we couldn't handle,&quot; Goldiggin answered.  &quot;Everyone's inside but us and Bristal.  She fell a bit behind and told us to go on ahead.  She should be here in a few minutes.&quot;<br><br>&quot;Very well,&quot; Arjaizen said.  &quot;I will wait here for her.  Join the others and let them know I have arrived.&quot;<br><br>&quot;Okay, but I don't think they're gonna throw a party or anything,&quot; the druid warned.  &quot;They were pretty ticked when you left with no explanation.&quot;<br><br>The Erudite laughed. &quot;Not to worry, they will understand shortly.  Go and tell them.&quot;<br><br>&quot;I'm gone,&quot; Goldiggin answered, and ran into the cave.<br><br>---<br><br>&quot;WHERE IS SHE?&quot;  Bristal slammed the goblin against a boulder and slashed at it with her sword.<br><br>The Goblin dodged the sword, barely.  It was bleeding from several wounds, and had two broken ribs, but wouldn't give the dwarf the answer she sought. &quot;You will find her in the Eye, just before she starts to fry,&quot; it taunted.<br><br>&quot;No poetry!&quot; She swung wildly in her rage, and the goblin managed to stab her with it's spear.  It was the third goblin she had fought, two goblin corpses lay nearby.  Perhaps she took on too much, but her anger carried her through, though her injuties were brutal as well, and her armor was in tatters.  With a final swing of her sword, she beheaded the goblin, and it fell to the ground. &quot;No poetry.&quot;<br><br>With her body bleeding, and her eyes burning, she stalked over to the last goblin, standing near the edge of the great lava pit, lulled into a trance from a spell.  She slapped it with the side of her blade, and it snapped to awareness, finding itself with the point of a razor-sharp sword at its throat.  &quot;Your friends are already dead, and I'm only gonna ask this once,&quot; <br>Bristal scowled.  &quot;Where... is... she?&quot;<br><br>The goblin bared its teeth, and in dwarvish, said only one word, &quot;Vengeance.&quot;<br><br>&quot;Suit yourself.&quot;  With a smash of her shield, Bristal knocked the goblin backward.  It's foot slipped on the edge of the pit, then it toppled beyond, falling until it was consumed by the molten rock below.<br><br>She bound her wounds as best she could, and cast healing spells to take care of most of her remaining damage.  She was tempted to simply lay hands upon herself, but that power was long to return, and she might need it later.  Finished with her healing, with grim determination Bristal set off towards the cave entrance to Solusek's Eye.  <br><br>---<br><br>Arjaizen spotted a figure approaching from a short distance away.  It wasn't Bristal, the figure was too tall, and too thin for its height.  Though his race was hard to determine from the distance, his garb and bow seemed to indicate a ranger.  As he got closer, the wizard could see the clasp on the ranger's cloak:  The symbol of the Fallen Wolves.<br><br>&quot;All hail the Fallen Wolves&quot; the Erudite called out, and the ranger responded in kind.  His name was Alerivers, and he had tracked the party since Nektulos Forest, having heard of the mission in a Freeport Tavern.  (News and gossip traveled quite quickly in the League of Antonican Bards.)  Their introductions complete, they heard a scrambling sound coming up the rock path towards the cave.<br><br>As Alerivers pulled back an arrow in his bow, a familiar helm appeared.  Bristal came into view, and greeted her guildmates.  &quot;Hi Arj, nice to see you could make it,&quot; not quite succeeding in hiding a trace of sarcasm<br><br>&quot;Yes, yes, I understand your frustration,&quot; Arjaizen responded, &quot;but I believe you are about to forgive me... especially considering the condition I see you are in.&quot;  He opened the large bag, withdrew a small fine steel breastplate, and handed it to the dwarf.  &quot;I have a few other pieces for you as well.  Greaves, bracers, pauldrons, and belt.  They took some time to make, and no small amount of coin, but for the mission at hand, perhaps they are necessary?&quot;<br><br>Bristal's eyes were wide in amazement.  The gleaming armor was beautiful.  &quot;I'll pay you back in full, no problem,&quot; she said.  &quot;Arj, this is great.  Thanks.&quot;<br><br>&quot;What are friends for,&quot; Arjaizend responded, &quot;if not to take care of each other, hmmm?&quot;<br><br>Bristal changed from her damaged armor to the shining plate.  As she finished fastening the last buckle, she drew her sword and said, &quot;Okay... let's go.&quot;<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Fri Apr 12 16:59:43 2002</em></p>&nbsp;<br><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>Arjaizen Izrhume<br>40th Circle Wizard of Erudin<br>Fallen Wolves</td></tr>
