	     <form action=/cgi-bin/mrate.pl name=f101665733080319>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=101665733080319>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=101665733080319>Freedom of Trade</a> <a id=fs8 href=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=101665733080319#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Wed, Mar 20th 3:51 PM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=93845><span id=Sage>Arjaizen</span></a><br><b><span id=Sage>Sage</span></b><br><span id=notbold>197 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [4.79]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>One of the nice things about being in a place with no day or night was that nothing ever closed.&nbsp;&nbsp;In spite of all the annoyances Arjaizen had encountered thus far - especially in Shadow Haven, he did enjoy the fact that if he wanted to be awake, there would always be something he could do, and someplace to eat or drink.<br><br>He had no idea what time it was, though since he had been up for over twelve hours, he decided to call it &quot;dinner time.&quot;  Across the table in the Bazaar's tavern/cafe sat a Half-elf of indeterminate age, though Arjaizen supposed she looked all of 25 in Human (or Erudite) terms.  He had not yet managed to find the Wood-elf Goldiggin his son had told him about, but this comely lass was pleasant enough company.  And, he had seen with his own eyes, quite proficient with blade and bow.<br><br><br>As they ate their dinner (something called &quot;rockhopper steaks,&quot;  a bit tough, but quite tasty,)  The wizard commented on something the Half-elf ranger had said.<br><br>&quot;Hold on a moment, Kaydwenn,&quot; he said. &quot;You're telling me that the administrators of Shadow Haven actively discourage so-called 'vigilantes' from attacking the bandit camps?&quot;<br><br>Kaydwenn took a sip of her wine and nodded.  &quot;They say such things are best left to the Haven Guards,&quot; she replied.  The ranger rolled her eyes at that, adding, &quot;Of course, the guards never go further than the end of the bridge to the Paludal Caverns.  Traders and travelers are left to fend for themselves... except the Havenite trading guild, of course.&quot;<br><br>A broad mischevous grin started to spread across the Erudite Wizard's face.  &quot;So the administrators of the town... the town that treats us as though we were disease-ridden parasites, would be upset and annoyed should we decide to try and eliminate the attacks of these 'Recondite Bandits'.  They'd get more visitors, and more traders... traders they would have no control over because they are not part of their guild system.  Would that be a fair assessment?&quot;<br><br>Kaydwenn swallowed her mouthful of steak and tilted her head in thought for a moment. &quot;Yes, that's about the size of it.&quot;<br><br>Arjaizen rubbed his hands together and started to chuckle.  &quot;Outstanding,&quot; he snickered, with a twinkle in his eye.  &quot;Absolutely outstanding.  Shall we start tomorrow?&quot;<br><br>The ranger raised her glass and answered, &quot;I didn't come here to sightsee.&quot;<br><br>Touching his glass to hers, the wizard proposed a toast.  &quot;To free trade.&quot;<br><br>Kaydwenn responded in kind.  &quot;To free trade,&quot; she responded, &quot;and tourism.&quot;<br><br>&quot;Yes, of course,&quot; Arjaizen agreed, &quot;and tourism.&quot;</p>&nbsp;<br><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>Arjaizen Izrhume<br>40th Circle Wizard of Erudin<br>Fallen Wolves</td></tr>
