<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=/cgi-bin/mrate.pl name=f101527806148159>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=101527806148159>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=101527806148159>A New World</a> <a id=fs8 href=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=101527806148159#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Mon, Mar 4th 4:42 PM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=93845><span id=Sage>Arjaizen</span></a><br><b><span id=Sage>Sage</span></b><br><span id=notbold>197 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [4.79]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>The wizard cut open the envelope and opened the letter inside.&nbsp;&nbsp;It had been several months since he had last spoken to his son, and he was eager to hear of his latest adventures.  He knew of Bejaizen's successful escort mission to High Keep, of course, and that he had subsequently gone to Luclin at the behest of Lord Bulrious.  As he read through his son's letter, he reveled in the good works he had accomplished, but frowned upon nearing the end of the paladin's message.<br><br>-----<br><br>...I met with great prejudice in Shadow Haven, Father.  I don't know how to make further progress in proving my reputation with the local residents.  Even those Havenites whose ancient ancestors called Odus their home shunned me.  Thankfully, there are a few folk there who are more tolerant.  Perhaps if enough of our brethren came there to combat such enemies as the bandits of the Paludal Caverns, and the strange aliens of the Netherbian Lair, the locals will see past their bigotry and realize the error of their ways.<br><br>While I would like to find out, I'm afraid my crusade against the kobold hordes must go on.  I have returned to Norrath and the Stonebrunt Mountains and once again carry Erudin's banner against the vermin that would overrun our fair island.  I wish you could have been home when I arrived, but I understand you have your own duties to attend to.  <br><br>Should your duties permit, please go to Luclin yourself and join with the Wood Elf Goldiggin.  I am sure the two of you would do well together, and perhaps together, you could build some trust amongst the people of Shadow Haven.  Just be careful of the Recondite Bandits.  They are formidable enemies, even for one such as yourself.  Consider it an opportunity to bring glory to the name of the 7th Legion.<br><br>Fare well, and good journeys, Father.<br><br>In the Tranquil's service, <br><br>Bejaizen<br><br>-----<br><br>The wizard folded the paper neatly and stored it carefully in a locked box guarded by magic wards and runes.  None but the family could open the box without destroying the contents, nor place messages within without their being marked as tainted.  <br><br>Arjaizen was pleased that his son had returned safely from Luclin, and was once again cleansing the island of its Kobold infestation.  <br><br>Go to Luclin, eh?  The thought appealed to him, as did the thought of fighting alongside another member of the 7th.  It had been too long since he and Cona had parted ways, and he had heard good things about this Goldiggin fellow.  Besides, he had tired of annoying the starched robes of the three towers, and found that it was now they who were getting on -his- nerves, and that would never do.<br><br>He got his traveling gear organized, then wrote a letter to his children, telling them of his plans, and how to reach him.  Taking hold of his Staff of Writhing, he set out towards the Wizard's spires of the Toxxulia Forest.  As he left his house, the door closed of its own accord, and with a shower of sparkles, it was sealed against all but the most powerful of magics.<br><br>As he stood at the top of steps leading to the tunnel to Toxxulia, he turned and looked back at the city of Erudin.  While rising through 24 Tests of the Circles, he had traveled almost everywhere on the three old world contintents, and had never seen one to match its beauty.  He wondered what wonders awaited him on the moon of Luclin?  <br><br>Walking down the tunnel, he chuckled to himself.  Few wizards would understand his trekking on foot to the spires.  He could, after all, gate there in an instant.  He preferred to afford himself some exercise though, believing that fitness would serve him well should he be forced to defend himself in melee combat. <br><br>With a cheery &quot;fare well&quot; to the Sentinels at the Toxxulia Forest entrance to Erudin, he made his way through the mist towards the forest's wizard spires.  A new world awaited.</p>&nbsp;<br><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>Arjaizen Izrhume<br>40th Circle Wizard of Erudin<br>Fallen Wolves</td></tr>
