<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=/cgi-bin/mrate.pl name=f101242084836614>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=101242084836614>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=101242084836614>The Moonhunter</a> <a id=fs8 href=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=101242084836614#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Wed, Jan 30th 4:02 PM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=93845><span id=Sage>Arjaizen</span></a><br><b><span id=Sage>Sage</span></b><br><span id=notbold>197 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [5.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Alone at the peak of the hill, Barrik looked off into the distance towards Qeynos.&nbsp;&nbsp;Although he could not see the once-great city from there, he could see the black smoke rising into the sky.  For three days, the fires had been burning, and the hills had been crawling with trolls, searching for more &quot;cattle,&quot; as they referred to the other smaller races.<br><br>&quot;Cattle,&quot; the gray-haired ranger grumbled to himself as he looked into a small bag.  Inside the bag were over thirty troll ears, one from each of the creatures he had slain since they first started showing up in the Qeynos Hills.  &quot;I wonder how many I have to kill before they come up with a new name for us?&quot;<br><br>Off to the west, the sun dropped slowly over the horizon.  The trolls would soon be coming back out to hunt... and be hunted.<br><br>He wandered through the rolling hills, always camouflaged, and always with great stealth.  He came across a troll or two every now and again.  None survived the encounter with his bow, axe, and lash.  Luclin was at its peak, and another half-dozen ears had been added to his bag, another half-dozen troll corpses littered the hills.  Too many... but nowhere near enough.<br><br>The moonlight glittered off the blade of his axe as he cleaned the off the green troll blood, and he looked upwards at the shining jewel that made up part of his namesake.  He cast a spell, and faded from sight.  The Moonhunter set back to the task of avenging his hills, his home, his brothers and sisters of Karana.<br><br>It was just over two hours and another four ears later when he heard a familiar bellow.  A bear was fighting for its life.  Nature's way it was, and generally not something the rangers of Surefall would interfere with, but this bear was not fighting another of Tunare's creatures.  Barrik heard the twisted, horrible laughter of trolls mixed with the howls of pain from the bear.  His eyes narrowed and his mouth curled with hatred as he ran towards the battle, heedless of the noise his running would make.  It was after all, nothing compared to the din of the troll's hideous laughter.<br><br>He neared the clearing and saw one of the protected of Surefall Glade, a rope securing it to a tree, three trolls poking it with spears, and singeing its fur with burning sticks.  Wasting no time, he cast a spell, and roots grew from the ground, entwining themselves around the legs of the troll nearest the bear.  when his friends saw the roots, they looked about, trying to find the source of the spell that had trapped one of their own.  <br><br>They may have seen Barrik in the darkness, had their fire not impaired their night vision.  As it was, he managed to entangle a second troll before his position was noticed.  The remaining troll charged him, holding a spiked club and screaming a battle cry.<br><br>One more spell was cast before the troll managed to reach Barrik, and the troll's skin began to blister and burn.  The spell was not much more than an annoyance, but it had the desired effect:  the troll's natural recuperative powers were negated for the time being.  <br><br>Barrik's axe flashed as he struck the troll, and suddenly the troll's attacks seemed to stop inches from the ranger's body.  Barrik swung his lash, and the troll choked as its throat was strangled.  <br><br>The troll was strong, but the ranger of Karana seemed posessed.  He hacked without mercy and gave no quarter.  Though he suffered a few wounds of his own, his attacks were relentless.  One of the trapped trolls broke free of the roots and came to his compatriot's aid.  Barrik ignored him and concentrated on his first opponent, who quickly fell lifeless to the ground.   <br><br>The second troll was stronger than the first.  He knocked the ranger to the ground near an oak tree, and swung his axe at Barrik's head.  Barrik rolled to the side, and the blade of the axe buried itself 3 inches deep in the trunk of the oak.  As the troll struggled to free his blade, Barrik re-cast his grasping roots spell on the remaining troll, so he would not be double-teamed a second time.  To help his chances, (and since the axe blade had not yet been freed from the tree,) Barrik cast a couple of healing spells upon himself, then a flame lick upon the troll just as the beast's axe came loose.<br><br>As the troll turned to Barrik, the ranger cast spells to ignite the air about it.  In between strikes with his axe and lash, he would cast the ignite spell again and again, until the troll, with a final scream, collapsed in a charred heap.<br><br>Turning to the last troll, Barrik spoke for the first time.  In Trollish, he growled, &quot;You like to play with bears, do you?  Go ahead... enjoy it.  But let me make it more interesting.&quot;<br><br>Stowing his weapons, He drew his carved oak bow.  Nocking a bone-shafted arrow, he fired, and the arrow buried itself in the troll's left arm.  A second did the same to his right.  Casting a snare spell to slow the troll's movements once the roots holding it gave way, he then nocked a third arrow, and fired it into the troll's left leg, followed by another to it's right.  A fifth arrow went into his bow, and he turned to the bear and took careful aim.  <br><br>The arrow flew straight and true, and the rope trapping the bear was cut through.  The enraged bear leaped upon the helpless troll, quickly rending it to pieces.<br><br>Barrik used the last of his mana to heal the bear.  He'd get to his own wounds soon enough.  Brushing the now-calm creature's fur, he sent it on its way.  There were just two more things to be done...<br><br>The iron glowed red as he pulled it from the fire.  The air stank from the smell of burning troll flesh, but the breeze would quickly disperse it.  Each troll forehead was branded in turn, then Barrik sliced an ear from each one.  He looked carefully at each forehead, making sure the brand was easy to distinguish.  A crescent moon, overlaid by a crossed bow and arrow.  <br><br>Enough time had passed for him to recoup a small amount of mana.  With a grim smile, the Moonhunter cast one final spell, and disappeared as the sun began to rise.<br><br>Barrik Moonhunter, Ranger of Karana<br><br>---<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Thu Jan 31 05:42:10 2002</em></p>&nbsp;<br><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>Arjaizen Izrhume<br>40th Circle Wizard of Erudin<br>Fallen Wolves</td></tr>
