<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=/cgi-bin/mrate.pl name=f10112029282521>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=10112029282521>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=10112029282521>Know Thine Enemies, Part 8</a> <a id=fs8 href=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=10112029282521#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Wed, Jan 16th 12:42 PM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=93845><span id=Sage>Arjaizen</span></a><br><b><span id=Sage>Sage</span></b><br><span id=notbold>197 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [5.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>The five trolls hid under the South Qeynos dock, waiting for their chance to sneak aboard the ship heading to Odus.&nbsp;&nbsp;The captain of the boat was not picky about who he carried, as long as they paid the fare, and didn't cause any trouble on his vessel.  <br><br>As they waited, the shaman Murgut listened to the group of Erudites that were disembarking.  They were speaking in Erudian, of course, but Murgut was chosen by Emperor Pusbag to lead this group specifically because he spoke that language fairly well.  If he understood them correctly, their target was supposed to be with them, but wasn't.  Something else... porting?  Him?  Another?  Someone was being sent to North Karana to join these Erudites, but he couldnt tell whether or not it was the paladin they were seeking.<br><br>If they went to Odus, and the paladin was ported to North Karana, they'd have no chance of getting him.  If they went to North Karana instead, and someone else was sent to join these peanut heads, they'd have to come all the way back.  The Emperor would no doubt be equally displeased with the delay in his capture.  They would have to split up.  <br><br>Murgut decided to send two of the warriors to North Karana.  The Paladin was only one weak peanut head, after all.  What chance would he have against two trollen warriors?  Murgut would continue on to Odus with the shadow knight and the remaining warrior.  He'd need all the magical support he could get in Erudin, and he didn't dare send the knight away.<br><br>&quot;Dox, Praak, You go to North Karana,&quot; he said in his own tongue.  &quot;The paladin may be traveling north on the road to the gypsy camp. You know what he looks like, don't you?&quot;<br><br>Praak nodded.  &quot;Yah.  Blue chain.  Brown shield wit tree.  Icy sword.  Praak knows.&quot;<br><br>&quot;Good.  If you find him, catch him and bring him to Grobb,&quot; the shaman told them.  &quot;DON'T kill him.  The Emperor wants him alive.&quot;<br><br>Dox grinned. &quot;yah, we get 'im.  We go.&quot;  He turned to head up to the beach stairs to South Qeynos.<br><br>&quot;Wait,&quot; the shaman ordered.  &quot;Do you want to be killed?  The guards will cut you down in seconds!&quot;  He cast spells upon them to make them as swift as wolves, then reached into a pouch and pulled out a small artifact given to him by the Emperor.  Uttering arcane phrases, the shaman waved his hands over the device.  It glowed softly in response.  Then, he touched each warrior in turn, and they disappeared from view.<br><br>&quot;Now you can go.  Hurry out the north gate to the city.  The invisibility will not last long, but you should have plenty of time to get well clear of the city walls.  Go.  Go quickly.&quot;<br><br>As the warriors' footprints tracked off along the beach, Murgut and the rest of the group quietly made their way aboard the boat, which shortly cast off from the docks.  One way or another, they would get this paladin, and bring him to the Emperor.<br><br><br>---<br><br>As Bejaizen made his way north towards the gypsy camp and (he hoped,) the Erudite delegation, he tried to remember the lay of the land from the last time he had been here.  If he remembered correctly, the camp would be about an hour away, give or take a few minutes.  Assuming the delegation was on schedule, he had a chance of getting there on time.  He hoped for the best and pressed on.<br><br>Rounding a bend, he saw a massive troll in crude, mismatched metal armor.  In his hand was a huge sword with a bronze blade.  &quot;Move aside, troll,&quot; the paladin warned.  &quot;I have business to the north, and no time for delays.&quot;<br><br>The troll did not move.  Instead, it grinned, showing a jagged row of yellow teeth.  &quot;Empruh sez brinz ya ta Grobb.  You come, or weez whomp yaz.&quot;<br><br>Bejaizen's eyes narrowed.  &quot;We?&quot;  Suddenly, he heard a twig snap behind him.  Turning about, he saw another equally large troll warrior behind him.  The troll had said &quot;Emperor.&quot;  So these were sent by Pusbag.  That confirmed what he suspected since Sentinel Creot told him of the Iksar in the Toxxulia Forest.  The King of the Trolls and the Queen of the Iksar were both after him.  That was a problem for the future.  For the present, he had two trolls to deal with.  <br><br>As the one in front of him started to come forward, Bejaizen cast a spell upon the troll behind.  That one's eyes glazed over, as though he was in some sort of a stupor.  His partner looked confused.<br><br>&quot;Dox?  C'mon,&quot; he urged.  &quot;Let's get 'im,&quot; he yelled, but Dox remained motionless.  <br><br>As Praak yelled at his partner, Bejaizen attacked.  His first strike hit the troll hard, deeply cutting into Praak's arm.  As the troll turned to counter, Bejaizen slowly moved further away from Dox, so as not to disturb his lulled mind.  Praak's attention was now fully on the paladin, as he tried to cut him in two with his huge blade.<br><br>Strike for strike, Bejaizen was overmatched, and he quickly concluded that were he fighting both of the trolls at once, he would surely have been subdued in moments.  However, he used his spells to good advantage, rooting Praak in place and healing himself when he needed to.  Though his natural regeration abilities allowed the troll to gradually heal himself, it was not fast enough to compensate for the wounds he received at the Peacekeeper's hands.  <br><br>In a fog, Dox daydreamed about troll women combing his ear hair and feeding him hot and spicy toelings as he lay in a hot mud bath.  Slowly, the sounds of battle intruded on his reverie, and the dream lifted.  Shaking his head, he turned toward the sound, and saw Praak fall to the ground as the Erudite pulled his crystal blade from the troll's torso.  Dox screamed in rage and raised his sword high.  As he charged Bejaizen, the paladin waved an arm through the air and spoke strange words.  Suddenly, Dox found his feet stuck to the ground!  As he struggled, Bejaizen cast more spells, and Dox could see the Erudite's injuries quickly healing.<br><br>The battle would be close, Bejaizen knew.  Were it not for the lion he had to fight earlier in the day, he would still have the ability to lay hands upon himself.  If he could do that, this fight would be child's play.  As it was, he prayed the Tranquil would grant her favor to him, and allow him to prevail.<br><br>Suddenly, the root broke, and Dox charged him.  His injuries were not fully healed, but he was running low on mana, he was sure.  It would have to do...<br><br>Bejaizen followed the same strategy as with Praak for as long as his mana held out.  Finally, it ran dry, and the Erudite and the Troll were left toe-to-toe.  Sparks flew from swords as the blades struck, and blood, both red and green, streamed from where they touched flesh.  Dox raised a huge fist high, and slammed the paladin to one knee.  He then grabbed his sword with both hands, brought it over his head, and with a loud battle cry, brought it down in a deadly arc.  <br><br>With all his strength, Bejaizen quickly raised his sword to a high guard position to counter the troll's blow.  When the warrior's bronze weapon struck the paladin's crystallized blade, it broke in two.  When the troll looked at his broken sword in stunned surprise, using the last of his strength Bejaizen slashed hard across the troll's waist, just under the plates of Dox's tunic.  The sword cut completely through Dox, and he fell to the ground in two pieces.<br><br>As he staggered to his feet, Bejaizen heard more footsteps behind him.  Badly wounded, out of mana, and with no way to lay hands upon himself, he knew that another fight would surely be his last.  Still, he turned with defiance, his lip curling in a sneer.  His life would not come cheaply.<br><br>---<br><br>The Erudite delegation made their way through the North Karana plains.  While there was the occasional small hillock here and there to break the monotony, for the most part the plains were flat as a table.  <br><br>Were it not for the sudden storm that came up as they were on the boat from Odus to Antonica, they would have already been at the gypsy camp.  As it was, they were lucky to be only a few hours behind schedule.  <br><br>The storm had set them back by two days, but Jorrel, one of two paladins to Prexus escorting the delegation, happened to see a Human wizard that was an old friend at the Lion's Mane in Qeynos.  His friend said he was gating to North Karana the following morning, and kindly offered to take the delegation along, free of charge.  The clerics were somewhat taken aback by the offer, but were also pleased to accept.  Thankfully, their journey from the spires to meet up with Izrhume at the gypsy camp had been uneventful.  <br><br>Off in the distance, the unmistakable sound of clanging swords signalled the end of uneventfulness.  Drawing his sword, he waved the party to a halt.  &quot;Hold here, he ordered.  &quot;I will scout ahead.&quot;<br><br>&quot;Nonsense,&quot; replied Pellren, the cleric that was one of the two Quellious delegates.  &quot;There is safety in numbers, is there not?  We should stay together.&quot;<br><br>&quot;No,&quot; Jorrel replied.  &quot;The safe passage of the delegation to High Keep is of paramount importance.  We don't know what's up there, and I will not risk the success of our mission for any reason.  Wait here. I will tell you if it's safe.&quot;<br><br>Jorrel ran up the road, and around the bend.  As he approached the corner, he heard a blood curdling scream.  Turning the corner, he saw carnage all about, and in the center of it all, slowly rising to his feet, the lone scowling figure of a blue-mailed Erudite, sword dripping green blood.  Jorrel stopped in his tracks, and said quietly, &quot;By the Ocean Lord, Izrhume...&quot;<br><br>Seeing Jorrel, Bejaizen relaxed.  &quot;Jorrel... Thank the Tranquil,&quot; he gasped, and slowly staggered toward him.  As the Peacekeeper got closer, his strength left him entirely, and he fell forward into Jorrel's arms.<br><br>Bejaizen Izrhume<br>22nd Rank Paladin to Quellious<br>7th Legion, The Nameless<br>---<br><br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Wed Jan 16 13:10:35 2002</em></p>&nbsp;<br><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>Arjaizen Izrhume<br>40th Circle Wizard of Erudin<br>Fallen Wolves</td></tr>
