	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=101016556796125>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=101016556796125>Know Thine Enemies, part 7</a> <a id=fs8 href=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=101016556796125#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Fri, Jan 4th 12:32 PM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=93845><span id=Sage>Arjaizen</span></a><br><b><span id=Sage>Sage</span></b><br><span id=notbold>197 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [5.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>It was a long walk from the wizard spires of North Karana to the gypsy camp.&nbsp;&nbsp;Traveling alone made it seem even longer.  Bejaizen wished he'd asked his new friend, the Wood Elf Goldiggin to come along, but while he was sure the young (or at least young-looking) druid would have come if asked, Bejaizen knew he'd be bored to tears at the council meeting.  Besides, he wasn't all that certain the rest of the delegation would be particularly pleased to have an outsider along for the trip, even if he -could- cast spells to hasten the journey.  <br><br>Several hours north of the spires, he heard what sounded like a cry for help coming from the other side of a small hill.  Drawing his sword, he dashed to the crest of the hill.  Looking down, he could see a griffawn attacking a halfling, who was definitely getting the worst of the battle.  He ran closer, close enough to cast healing spells upon the halfling, and he cast several in a row, to try and help keep the overmatched fellow alive.  Try as he might though, his heals could not keep up with the pounding the poor halfling was taking.  That strategy would only delay his death, not prevent it.<br><br>Targeting the griffawn, Bejaizen cast a spell to set off a blinding flash in its eyes.  The beast then started flailing out erratically.  Giving the halfling another heal, Bejaizen shouted, &quot;Run!  The guards are to the north.  Go as quickly as you can!  I will hold off the monster!&quot;<br><br>Terror in his eyes, the halfling turned and ran, yelling his thanks over his shoulder as he did.  A moment later, Bejaizen could see the griffawn returning, still bent on attacking the halfling.  He cast another blinding spell on it, but this time, it did not seem to be affected... except that it seemed now to understand the greater threat (and perhaps, the better meal,) was the armored Erudite now taunting it from afar.<br><br>&quot;Come, do your worst, foul beast!&quot;  Bejaizen roared out his challenge.  &quot;Have at me, if you dare!&quot;  <br><br>Screeching an angered reply, the griffawn came.  With frightening speed, it closed on the paladin, needle-sharp claws extended menacingly.  As it reached him, it slashed Bejaizen with those claws, cutting into his flesh through the links of his armor.  As it pulled away to make another pass, the injured Peacekeeper swung his sword in an unerring arc, but was only able to strike his attacker with a glancing blow.  <br><br>For long minutes, the battle was joined.  Bejaizen was badly wounded, but so was his opponent.  Seeing the fatigued paladin's sword drop low, the griffawn instinctively attacked his head, knocking off his helm, and putting a deep gash in his ample forehead.  As he staggered back in pain, Bejaizen blindly swung his sword upward...<br><br>There are times when luck can be more important than skill, and this time, at least partially, was one of them.  His blind swing slashed deep through the griffawn's side, slipped perfectly between two ribs, and neatly sliced its heart in the process, killing it instantly.  Bejaizen's luck in this case was only partial because the creature, in death, landed on top of him, knocking him to the ground.  Were he still wearing his helm, this would have been no more than an annoyance.  As it was, when his head struck the ground (or more precisely, a large rock on the ground,) he was also struck unconscious, where since he could not be seen by travelers on the road, and since the halfling he rescued had no intention of pressing his luck by returning, he remained for the next sixteen hours.<br><br>When the weight of the dead griffawn's carcass was dragged off his body, Bejaizen was jostled awake.  His groan of pain was greeted by a roar, and his eyes snapped open instantly.  Finding himself face-to-face with a large, and apparently very hungry, lion, he said a quick prayer to the Tranquil and lay hands upon himself.  In an instant, every injury he had mended itself in a blur of blue light.  Revitalized, he took up his sword and spun to his feet as the lion leaped to the attack.<br><br>A flick of his wrist, and the lion's right foreleg was sliced off in mid-leap.  Sidestepping, he then sliced his sword down the length of its body as it fell, opening a three-foot wound.  The animal tried to run, but Bejaizen quickly caught it, and put the suffering creature out of its misery.<br><br>As he bent over to pick up his helm, Bejaizen saw the first glimmerings of the dawn beginning to break.  Once again, he had to hurry to try and get to his destination in time!  By his reckoning, it would be late morning before he reached the gypsies.  He prayed to the Tranquil that he PLEASE be allowed to reach the camp before the delegation, and chewing on an iron ration as he went, he hurried off along the road to the north.<br><br>Bejaizen Izrhume<br>21st Rank Paladin of Quellious<br>7th Legion, The Nameless<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Fri Jan  4 12:47:37 2002</em></p>&nbsp;<br><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>Arjaizen Izrhume<br>40th Circle Wizard of Erudin<br>Fallen Wolves</td></tr>
