<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=/cgi-bin/mrate.pl name=f100999636444428>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=100999636444428>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=100999636444428>Know Thine Enemies, part 6</a> <a id=fs8 href=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=100999636444428#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Wed, Jan 2nd 1:32 PM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=93845><span id=Sage>Arjaizen</span></a><br><b><span id=Sage>Sage</span></b><br><span id=notbold>197 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [5.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>The wizard pored over the ageless text intently.&nbsp;&nbsp;The dialect of the ancient Combine tongue was very strange, and hard to decipher, even for one such as himself, who had spent decades learning every known variation of the old empire's language.  It was hard to be sure, but this document seemed to tell of the Combine's exodus to the moon of Luclin.  This verse, the &quot;stairway to the river of flame,&quot; followed by the &quot;eternal guardian of fire,&quot; intrigued him.  Was it even possible?  The holy documents used similar words to refer to the entrance to the Plane of Sun, home to Solusek Ro.  He looked out his window at the setting moon.  COuld it be up there?  He would need to...<br><br>(knock, knock, knock)<br><br>&quot;Yes, yes, I'm coming.&quot;  Annoyed, he looked away from his papers, got up from his desk and went to the door.  Opening it, he found a blue-clad Peacekeeper, sheathed sword at his side.  His nose wrinkled in irritation.  A savage.  &quot;What do you want? I'm very busy and do not wish to be disturbed.&quot;<br><br>&quot;My apologies, learned one,&quot; the paladin said with a bow.  &quot;I am Bejaizen Izrhume, of the Peacekeepers.  I was directed to come to you for transport to the North Karana spires.&quot;<br><br>&quot;I have no time for such nonsense,&quot; the wizard answered.  &quot;My studies are far more important than such trivial matters.  Begone,&quot; he said, and began to close the door to his quarters.<br><br>&quot;Of course,&quot; the paladin responded. &quot;I'll just let Ghanlin know your studies couldn't be disturbed.  He must have been mistaken that you would be able to take care of this for him.  He'll certainly understand.  Don't worry about it a bit.&quot;  He was turning to leave, when the door opened again.<br><br>&quot;Ghanlin?  Oh, yes... the Portal to North Karana,&quot; the wizard scowled, clearly upset.  He ushered the paladin into his study and said, &quot;Wait here, while I make the necessary preparations.&quot;<br><br>He wandered into another room and began his meditations, committing to memory the spells needed to bring both himself and the paladin to North Karana, and to gate himself back to his quarters.  Why he needed to be bothered with this, he had no idea.  But Ghanlin's wishes on this matter were not to be trifled with.  Still, it irked him to be used as a taxi service for a paladin in this fashion.  All the worse that it had to be -this- paladin.  Since Arjaizen's son was a sword-swinging savage, he could only assume the insanity had been passed down from generation to generation, perhaps even in a more virulent form.  He only hoped it wasn't contagious.<br><br>Having finished his meditations, he returned to the study, where Bejaizen was looking over the titles on the bookcase.  &quot;Don't touch those,&quot; the wizard growled.  &quot;Stand close.&quot;<br><br>Weaving the portal spell caused the room to fill with shimmering spheres of light.  As they swirled about the two Erudites, suddenly the room seemed frozen in time.  Seconds later, Bejaizen found himself in the center of a group of Wizard spires.  A bit dazed, he shook his head to clear it, then turned to see where the wizard was.  As he did, he saw another flash of light as the wizard winked out of sight without another word to him.<br><br>&quot;Typical,&quot; he mused.  When one carried a sword in Erudin, those from the three towers tended to think of you as a lower life form, barely worthy of a second glance, never mind a pleasantry.  Thankfully, the casters he met outside the walls of the city seemed to be a bit more pragmatic where the utility of an armored compatriot was concerned.<br><br>Getting his bearings, he set out along the nearby path, heading north to the gypsy camp where he was to meet the Erudin delegation.  He would reach the camp by nightfall.  If all went well, the delegation would be arriving the following afternoon.  Plenty of time.<br><br>Bejaizen Izrhume<br>21st Rank Paladin of Quellious<br>7th Legion, The Nameless<br><br>---</p>&nbsp;<br><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>Arjaizen Izrhume<br>40th Circle Wizard of Erudin<br>Fallen Wolves</td></tr>
