	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=100921032136786>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=100921032136786>Know Thine Enemies, part 4</a> <a id=fs8 href=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=100921032136786#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Mon, Dec 24th 11:12 AM 2001</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=93845><span id=Sage>Arjaizen</span></a><br><b><span id=Sage>Sage</span></b><br><span id=notbold>197 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [5.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Charssk finished his meditations, opened his eyes, and rose to his feet. The raspy sound of the dying Sentinel gasping for breath was music to his ears, and he saw no reason to end it. The slow asphyxiation of the Erudite wasn't a full payment for the loss of his raiding party, but it would suffice, under the circumstances. With no voice, he couldn't cast his spells to heal his wounds. Indeed, having cast many spells during combat, Charssk doubted the Erudite had the mana left to cast at all, even if he had the voice to do it. Having already laid hands upon himself only moments before, by the time his deity deigned to grant him the power again, he would be long dead. With two broken limbs (the monk had seen to that,) he could not even crawl away for help. He grinned broadly, showing two huge rows of sharpened teeth at the dying sentinel. &quot;Embrace the darknesss, fool,&quot; he spat. &quot;It will claim you soon enough.&quot; <br><br>With that, he turned to the south, and headed towards the Heretic city. He would find the traitorous troll Rungupp, and show him the price of betrayal. Shortly, he came to the water's edge. The bridge was further towards the south, that much he knew, so he decided to swim rather than run. He would make better time that way, and it would be far easier to conceal himself in the dark water. <br><br>As he approached the bridge, he could see a figure crossing it through the fog. Perhaps adding another Erudite to the death toll would help assuage his anger... but no, first he would deal with the troll. One thing at a time. Business, then pleasure, as the humans liked to say. He went under the water and swam quickly under the bridge, leaving barely a ripple on the surface as he passed. <br><br>--- <br><br>Bejaizen moved across the bridge quickly, wanting to waste no time getting back to Erudin. The boat to Qeynos left in the morning, and if he missed it, he'd never reach High Keep in time for the meeting. As he crossed, out of the corner of his eye, he thought he caught some movement. He turned to look, and noticed a disturbance on the water's surface. It was very slight, like the passage of a caiman as it swam just under water, but there were no such creatures on Odus. Odd, but he had no time to wonder about it. He continued on his way, disappearing into the Toxxulian mists. <br><br>--- <br><br>The monk peered about, looking for the telltale glow of body heat in the distance. The troll was the largest thing he had seen in this forest, and the loudest. He shouldn't be hard to find. A familiar smell reached his nostrils, and his teeth bared involuntarily. &quot;Time to die, traitor,&quot; he thought to himself and he quietly crept towards the smell. Something was wrong, though. The smell wasn't quite right, Charssk sensed. Too much iron tang to it, as though... <br><br>He broke into the clearing, and saw the headless corpse on the ground. He let out a scream of anger, knowing he had been cheated of his vengeance! By whom, though? Charssk searched the area carefully, trying to find some small clue of the troll's killer. The cuts on the troll were clean. He was killed by a weapon of great quality, that was sure, but that information did Charssk no good. He looked closer at the corpse, a great feat, considering the smell. Under one fingernail, he saw a splinter. Pulling it out, he turned it over in his fingers. He held it close to his nose, and smelled it. The smell reminded him of home... this wood was Rock Cypress. That tree was only found in the swamps of Kunark. <br><br>He pulled the parchment from his pouch, and looked at the design of the shield carried by the Izrhume, the paladin called Bejaizen. He carried a targ shield, crafted in New Sebilis. Could it be? How supremely ironic that would be. He hissed in frustration, knowing that yet again, his goals were being thwarted. His eyes narrowed. He would need a new raiding party. The Empress would not be happy with his report, but he at least comforted himself that unlike her predecessors, she rarely killed those who failed on missions, unless that failure was through incompetence. He hoped she would not deem him a fool for his choices. <br><br>--- <br><br>The sun was coming up, though it was never seen under the tangled canopy of Toxxulian foliage. It did, however, brighten the gloom of the forest, for all but one living being in it. The sentinel gasped desperately for air, barely able to manage to pull in enough in one breath to be able to sustain him to the next. He knew he was dying, and his prayers to the Tranquil for deliverance seemed of no avail. His vision grew grayer, and he struggled to keep his eyes open. <br><br>He saw an out of focus figure emerge from the brush, and for a brief second, his hope flickered. Then his sight cleared slightly. The figure was a kobold runt. At least he'd be put out of his misery, but he had hoped that his last breath would not be due to being eaten alive. As the beast leaned over him, he saw it's jaws open wide to tear at his flesh... then its head came flying from its shoulders, and its body fell twitching at his side. <br><br>He heard the sound of a sheathing sword, and saw another figure kick the corpse away and kneel next to him. He could not make out the face, but the bluish gleam of his tunic was unmistakable. Only a handful of Erudite paladins wore the Midnight Sea mail, and he only knew of one currently on Odus. <br><br>Bejaizen saw the damage to the suffocating sentinel's throat, and knew he must act quickly. He could not lay hands upon him, that power had been used a few short hours ago to save a dwarven warrior that was near death in the Warrens. But perhaps he had gained enough mana to save the sentinel's life... He murmured a prayer and lightly touched the sentinel's neck. A blue light sparkled about him as healing powers flowed into his dying comrade. He saw the larynx mend itself, and air rushed into the sentinal's lungs. <br><br>&quot;Bejaizen, thank the Tranquil,&quot; he gasped, then let out a cry of pain as his movement caused his broken bones to shake. <br><br>&quot;Easy, Creot,&quot; the paladin said quietly. &quot;I need to splint these broken bones of yours, and bind your wounds. Then perhaps I can heal you enough so we can get you home.&quot; <br><br><br>--- <br><br>It was midday when the two Erudites reached the tunnel to Erudin. The sentinels at the gate took care of their injured compatriot as Bejaizen bid him farewell. He rushed to the docks, hoping against hope to reach the boat before it set sail to Qeynos. <br><br>--- <br><br>Bejaizen, of the clan Izrhume <br>18th Rank Paladin to Quellious <br>7th Legion, The Nameless</p>&nbsp;<br><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>Arjaizen Izrhume<br>40th Circle Wizard of Erudin<br>Fallen Wolves</td></tr>
