<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=/cgi-bin/mrate.pl name=f100747714819824>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=100747714819824>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=100747714819824>Once an Officer</a> <a id=fs8 href=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=100747714819824#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Tue, Dec 4th 9:45 AM 2001</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=93845><span id=Sage>Arjaizen</span></a><br><b><span id=Sage>Sage</span></b><br><span id=notbold>197 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [4.80]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>The owner of the Centurion's insignia finished polishing it to a high luster, gently placed it into the small cloth-lined box, and closed the lid. Placing it in his footlocker at the 7th Legion headquarters in Halas, he turned to the mirror and affixed the equally polished legionary's insignia to the collar of his tunic. He straightened his tunic, squared his shoulders, and after a last wistful glance at the closed footlocker, turned on his heel and walked out the door.<br><br>Making his way to Scei's Tavern, he wondered about what might have been, but thrust the thoughts from his mind. Serving the greater good was what mattered, and it was more important that the Legion's officer corps was filled with the guild's best and brightest, not those who were merely good with a sword. He had done the right thing, of that he was certain. What others might think didn't matter.<br><br>He entered the cozy confines of the tavern, and sat at the bar. Looking about to see who was working today, he noticed Sonja taking care of a group of adventurers in the corner. An attractive enough girl, but one of the smaller barbarian women you were likely to see, Sonja was not one for combat, and working the tables of the tavern was fulfilling enough for her. Suddenly, he was startled by the sound of a hand slapping the ash wood bar top.<br><br>&quot;Hey, quit checkin' out the help, you letch. You're old enough to be her dad.&quot; Scei had an ear-to-ear grin, pleased that she'd managed to stop her fellow Legionnaire's heart for a brief moment. &quot;Nice to see ya, Barrik,&quot; she said. &quot;The usual?&quot;<br><br>The gray-bearded ranger nodded. &quot;Hi Scei, yah, that'll do fine... and a sandwich. Whatever isn't moving.&quot;<br><br>Scei opened the door to the kitchen and yelled to her cook. &quot;Hey Gunnar, one shaved mammoth steak sandwich. Load it up.&quot; Turning back to the bar, she took a stoneware mug, drew ale for Barrik and set it down in front of him. &quot;Here you go, pal,&quot; she said. Seeing a few new customers at the other end of the bar, she added, &quot;Duty calls,&quot; then turned to take care of them.<br><br>...<br><br>Barrik was halfway through his sandwich when he heard the distinctive sound of boot heels clicking together.<br><br>&quot;Hail, Sir!&quot; he heard a booming voice say. He turned to see the speaker, and saw a human warrior in meticulously cared-for armor. The warrior snapped him a crisp salute.<br><br>&quot;Well met, Dracoius,&quot; he responded. &quot;But you can skip the salute.&quot; Gesturing to his tunic collar, he added, &quot;I'm not an officer any more, remember?&quot;<br><br>His compatriot looked confused. &quot;But, you're still a Centurion, aren't you?&quot; he asked.<br><br>The half-elf shook his head. &quot;No, an officer has to have an office. When I gave up the Politico's position, the rank went with it. I'm just a grunt, my friend.&quot;<br><br>&quot;You must be very disappointed that you were not offered the position again by the new Caesar,&quot; Dracoius offered.<br><br>&quot;Actually, I'm relieved.&quot; He took a drink and set down his glass before continuing. &quot;Look, all I ever wanted to be in my life was a Legionnaire. One of the rangers in the Surefall guild was in the Legion, and he would tell me stories about the Legion's legends. I wanted to be part of that history. But an officer?<br><br>&quot;I work hard, and I do my duty. I'm at home in the fields and forests. I'm a doer, not a thinker, and officers need to be thinkers. Taking the Politico's position was a mistake on my part. But when Fortenbras offered it to me, I thought it was my duty to accept. Wasn't until later that I figured out I was the wrong guy for the job. As fate would have it, Fortenbras was never able to swear me in, so when Biffington was given the Caesar's title, it gave me the chance to do the right thing. Thankfully, Biffington saw what I saw - that I was in over my head.&quot;<br><br>&quot;Not many have the courage to admit their limitations,&quot; Dracoius mused. &quot;That was an honorable thing to do.&quot;<br><br>Barrik shrugged. &quot;I don't know. In a way, it was the most selfish thing I've ever done. Time will tell, I guess.&quot;<br><br>Laying a few silver pieces on the bar, he gave Scei a wave from across the room, and then turned back to Dracoius. &quot;Time to go, Drac. Got a long journey ahead of me.&quot;<br><br>&quot;Where are you off to?&quot; the warrior asked.<br><br>Barrik shrugged a second time, and pointed off in the general direction of southeast. &quot;Not sure... that way, perhaps.&quot;<br><br>Dracious snapped a sharp salute to Barrik as the ranger headed towards the door. Hearing the click of Dracoius' heels, Barrik stopped. Turning halfway about, he raised his left eyebrow as a question.<br><br>The warrior shrugged and said, &quot;All Legionnaires are deserving of a salute, my friend. Whatever rank you hold doesn't matter to me.&quot;<br><br>Barrik grinned in spite of himself and shook his head. Clenching his right fist and tapping himself on the chest just over his heart, he said, &quot;Thanks, Drac. Good journeys to you, my friend. See you around.&quot;<br><br>With that, he walked out the door, and disappeared into the swirling snows of Halas.<br> <br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Tue Dec&nbsp;&nbsp;4 09:51:10 2001</em></p>&nbsp;<br><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>Arjaizen Izrhume<br>40th Circle Wizard of Erudin<br>Fallen Wolves</td></tr>
