<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=/cgi-bin/mrate.pl name=f100688362318923>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=100688362318923>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=100688362318923>In the Gorge - Ch. 5: Father and Son</a> <a id=fs8 href=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=100688362318923#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Tue, Nov 27th 12:53 PM 2001</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=93845><span id=Sage>Arjaizen</span></a><br><b><span id=Sage>Sage</span></b><br><span id=notbold>197 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [4.60]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>(Not the climactic chapter, but it seemed a good way to make an introduction.&nbsp;&nbsp;It also fit in with the timeline.) -Arj<br><br>--------------<br><br>A hundred candles burned in the temple chamber where a dozen young men and women stood at a crisp attention.  Their studies had been long and arduous, their physical training near back-breaking, but it was now complete.  Twelve new paladins to Quellious the Tranquil were now ready to join the ranks of the Peacekeepers of Erudin.  Lining the room were 20 of the temple's Guardians, there to welcome the new brothers and sisters into their ranks.<br><br>Depnar Bulrious, leader of the Peacekeepers, his gleaming armor reflecting the light of the fivescore tongues of flame, glittered as the sky on a clear starry night as he moved down the line of his new Holy Warriors.  With a critical eye he appraised them, and finally gave a solemn nod.  When he spoke, it was quietly, but with a deep resonance that seemed to reach inside of all who listened, holding their attention firmly in its grasp.<br><br>"Holy Warriors of Peace," he began. "Words that seem on the surface to be a contradiction.  How can one fight for peace?  Such is how many misunderstand the teachings of the Tranquil.  Our battle is not with war itself, but with chaos, fear, hatred, and greed.  These things douse the flame of inner peace.<br><br>"We seek not worldly wealth, but to have what is needed, and to be thankful for the opportunity to help others have the same.  We seek not power, but the wit and might necessary to defend the weak and powerless.  We fight so that others may know peace without.  In so doing, we find our own within."<br><br>As he spoke, one of the new Peacekeepers reflected on that which brought him to this place...  <br><br>Erudites who chose to take up the sword were few and far between.  Though respected after a fashion for their dedication to their gods, They were still thought strange.  The children of Erud were of course intended to harness the eldritch forces of the universe and were the undisputed (to them, at least,) masters of their craft.  Those closest to their gods and wisest in their ways became the clerics of the temples, healing the bodies and spirits of all who came for their help.  Swords were distained by those who practiced their crafts in the three towers of the palace.<br><br>The tower of the Crimson Hands housed the school of Wizardry.  From that school came Arjaizen Izrhume, father to Bejaizen.  He was not one of the school's better students, to say the least.  His personality was unreserved and unrestrained.  He seemed to care little what others thought, which was probably a good thing, as most others thought him insane.<br><br>To the amazement of many, he managed to capture the attentions of Ashaura, a young cleric of Quellious, and they soon were wed.  Bejaizen was their first born.  Being the son of "Arjaizen the Insane" took a toll on the boy, and when Ashaura died giving birth to his sister Euara, the distance between son and father grew wider.<br><br>Bejaizen left his home at the age of fourteen to begin his training.  Wanting to honor his mother's spirit, he took to the Temple of Quellious, yet not to follow in her footsteps as an Acolyte of Peace.  For years, he had felt shame at how his father was thought of by the powers that were in Erudin.  Perhaps, having a touch of rebellion in him (he was, after all fourteen,) he wished to spite those who would judge him on his father's actions.  Knowing the priests revered the paladins, but the wizards distained them, he chose the path of the Peacekeeper.<br><br>Where his father struggled as a student, Bejaizen excelled.  He trained his body as few others would, and threw himself into his spiritual studies with abandon.  Finally, after six long years of training, study, and apprenticeship, it was over.<br><br>"...and so, it is with a great deal of pride, that I say, 'Welcome, Peacekeepers, and well done.'  May the Tranquil guide you and bring her peace to all about you."  Bulrious clasped the hand of each paladin in turn, and returned their salutes.  A small reception was held, after which Bejaizen found himself speaking with Leraena Shelyrak, high priestess to the Tranquil.<br><br>"You should go home now, Bejaizen," she counseled.  "Be with your family."<br><br>"My sister is in the Tower of the Crimson Hands, pursuing her own studies.  They would not release her for the ceremony, and she faces an apprentice's test tomorrow.  My father is home, but I doubt he even knew of the graduation."  Bejaizen looked at the ground. "I never told him.  I've spent six years pursuing a path wizards mock.  Why would he care?"<br><br>"He is a follower of the Tranquil," the priestess countered.  "That in and of itself is very rare among wizards.  And he wed one of us.  Perhaps he would provide us with another surprise.  Go.  If you are accepted, be thankful.  If not, you always have a home here."<br><br>He stood before the door of his childhood home.  Rarely occupied for the last several years (he and Euara being in their respective schools and their father traveling the world,) this night there was a glow coming from the windows.  He reached out to knock on the door, but it slowly swung open of its own accord.  As he entered, it closed behind him, and he heard his father's voice coming from the living room.<br><br>"Since when does a man need to knock on the door of his own home?  Has it been so long that you've forgotten who lives here?"  His father sat grinning from a chair by the fireplace.  "You are looking well, son.  It's good to see you."<br><br>Bejaizen nodded solemnly.  "Thank you, father.  You also appear in good health."<br><br>The wizard got up and went over to a table where stood two decanters and two wine glasses.  As he walked across the room, he asked, "What brings you home today?"<br><br>"I came to tell you... I graduated today.  I am no longer an apprentice, but a Peacekeeper."<br><br>"I know.  I was at your graduation."<br><br>Bejaizen looked confused. "How could you be?  I didn't see you.  I didn't tell you."<br><br>His father grinned.  "I am a wizard.  Few people are able to see me if I do not wish it so.  And did you really think I would not be checking on your progress?  Bulrious told me of your graduation day months ago."<br><br>Pouring one glass from each of the decanters he offered one glass to his son. "A toast, my son," he offered.<br><br>Shaking his head, Bejaizen demurred.  "No, Father, I do not drink alcohol."<br><br>Rolling his eyes, Arjaizen responded, "I know that. For the love of the Tranquil, have SOME faith in your old man.  Your glass has fruit juice."<br><br>"And yours," his son asked.<br><br>"The finest Elven wine I could find for the occasion.  I respect your beliefs son, but my Barbarian friends tell me that for a toast to count, there must be alcohol involved.  I didn't want to take a chance," he grinned.  "Ten thousand Barbarians could be wrong, but the Dwarves seem to agree with them.  Who am I to argue?"<br><br>Sighing, Bejaizen shook his head.  Nonetheless, he took the offered glass and raised it.<br><br>"To peace," Arjaizen toasted. "Your mother would have been proud."<br><br>"To peace," Bejaizen answered, and they drained their glasses.<br><br>"I have a gift for you, son.  Some things to help you in your journeys."  He walked over to a large chest, and opened it.  Inside were a number of pieces of armor.  Most had seen some use, but were in excellent repair.  Several were banded armor, a few leather, but Bejaizen was surprised to find almost a full set.  "I believe you will find they all fit.  Oh, there's one more piece."<br><br>At the bottom of the chest was a box, which he handed to his son.  Bejaizen opened it, and his eyebrows raised in surprise.  Inside the box was a finely made studded leather tunic, clearly new.  "Thank you, father...where did you buy this?"<br><br>"I didn't," the wizard answered.  "I made it.  The high and mightys in the Crimson Hands told me to learn a trade... so I've learned several, among them tailoring and smithing.  I hope you like it."<br><br>"It's excellent.  I'm surprised.  I thought you would be embarassed that I chose the way of the sword."  He added, "The casters of the palace think it undignified."<br><br>"Oh, please," his father snorted.  "As though the thoughts of the closed-minded stuffed robes in the towers concern me in the least anymore."  He smacked himself lightly in the forehead and said, "Oh... Can't forget the weapons."<br><br>"Weapons?"<br><br>"Of course.  No son of mine is going to battle with a piece of junk in his hand."  He reached into a closet and brought out a leather-bound scabbard.  "This two-handed sword is of fine steel.  An excellent blade, but not for all situations.  In tighter quarters, you'll need something smaller.  There are also some creatures that cannot be harmed by any weapon that is not enchanted in some way."  <br><br>Going to the closet again, he withdrew a second scabbard.  From this he drew a longsword with a blade the likes of which Bejaizen had never seen.  Looking like a translucent crystal, or perhaps ice, it almost seemed to glow.  "This is made from Velium, from the long-lost continent of Velious.  Should you run into a creature that cannot be harmed by the two-hander, use this."<br><br>Bejaizen was stunned.  "I don't know what to say."<br><br>"Just wear the armor with pride, and wield the weapons with honor," his father answered.  "I must go now, son.  There is a battle coming in the Citadel of Runnyeye, and the 7th Legion has been asked to help."<br><br>As Arjaizen began casting a gating spell to transport himself across the leagues to Rivervale, his son bid him goodbye. "Fare well, father, and thank you."<br><br>The spell complete, a glimmering portal began to form itself around the wizard.  Over the eerie sound of warping space he called, "Oh, one more thing, and most importantly:  Do good."<br><br>"You mean, 'do well,'" Bejaizen corrected.<br><br>As the portal closed about him, Arjaizen smiled one more time.  "No... Do good."  With a final flash, he was gone.<br><br>The new paladin stood alone, as he realized at last how different the reality of his father was from his memory.  A lone tear ran down one cheek.  "I will, father, I swear it."</p>&nbsp;<br><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>Arjaizen Izrhume<br>40th Circle Wizard of Erudin<br>Fallen Wolves</td></tr>
