</ul></td></tr></table>

<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=/cgi-bin/mrate.pl name=f100593329698106>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=100593329698106>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=100593329698106>In the Gorge - Ch. 3: United We Stand</a> <a id=fs8 href=/journal2.html?user=93845&mid=100593329698106#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Fri, Nov 16th 12:54 PM 2001</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=93845><span id=Sage>Arjaizen</span></a><br><b><span id=Sage>Sage</span></b><br><span id=notbold>197 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [5.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>"RUN!", Barrik shouted.&nbsp;&nbsp;"Withdraw to the tunnel, they won't fit inside!"<br><br>Marchant ran as fast as he was able, desperately trying to get to the relative safety of the Runnyeye tunnel before the five onrushing minotaurs could reach him.  Near the cave entrance, Barrik fired arrow after arrow at the lumbering beasts, hoping to slow them down.  As Marchant ran past, Barrik cast a spell on one of the minotaurs, then dashed into the tunnel just as the enraged group reached him.  <br><br>Running quickly down the corridor and around a bend, he stayed and took aim with his bow back down the tunnel.  The low ceiling and tight confines made his range extremely short, but they also prevented the minotaurs from coming down more than one at a time.  Even then, they would hardly be able to move, and certainly could not fight to any effect.  Though they were not exceptionally bright creatures, they knew suicide when they saw it, and did not try to follow.<br><br>Turning to look at his partner, Barrik frowned and asked, "Would you mind telling me what THAT was about?"<br><br>Still trying to catch his breath, Marchant gasped, "Ambush... two out in the open... struck one with a spell... tried to lure them...&#8221; He took a deep breath and managed to speak more clearly.  "When I turned, I saw the other three coming down from hiding.  All I could do was run to here."<br><br>"Well, I guess our friends are smarter than they look... not that that's very hard. Just try and be more careful.  Next time you might not make it.  Come on," the ranger said.  "They've run off.  Let's go claim our prize."<br><br>A confused look came across Marchant's face. "Prize?"<br><br>"Well, you don't think I was going to let you go through that for nothing, do you?", Barrik responded with a grin.  <br><br>He would say nothing more as they moved back down the tunnel to the entrance.  Sure enough, the minotaurs were gone.  The ranger could clearly see their tracks leading off to the north.  All but one, that is.  One minotaur remained, running off to follow its mates.  It tried to run, anyway.  For all the speed it was generating, one would think it was up to its knees in mud.  <br><br>The young paladin looked back and forth from the minotaur to Barrik, a questioning look on his face. "Snare spell?", he asked.<br><br>"Got it in one," Barrik answered.  "Shall we?"<br><br>Narrowing his eyes, Marchant responded with a steely, "Aye, we shall," and charged the lone minotaur, his sword held high.<br><br>Barrik cast a flame lick spell to enrage the creature, then nocked an arrow and let it fly as the minotaur turned to face its attackers.  He then quickly stowed his bow, drew his axe and short sword, and ran to the fray.  The combined swordplay of the two half-elves was too much for the beast, and it quickly fell to their blades.<br><br>The weapon used by the minotaur was a large axe, balanced for use with one hand.  It was extremely sharp and well made.  Barrik looked at the tarnished sword Marchant carried, and said, "Here, you take it.  It will certainly work better that that thing."<br><br>To his surprise, the paladin refused. "I do not use axes.  A paladin's weapon is his sword.  This one will have to do until I earn, or can make, a better one."<br><br>"When we are next in Rivervale, I will give you one of mine, then.  I have more than I can use, and any one would be an improvement over your sword."<br><br>"No," Marchant said proudly. "As I said, I will not be beholden to others.  I appreciate your offer, but if my own toil didn't earn it, I don't want it."<br><br>"I'll keep that in mind on your birthday," Barrik said under his breath as he put the axe in his pack.<br><br>"Excuse me?" <br><br>"Nothing, it wasn't important."<br><br>They fought side-by-side for most of the day, carefully avoiding large groups, but noting their encampments.  When they found one alone, or two together, they would attack, with spells, swords, and bow, and prevailed in every battle.  Between the two of them, they had sufficient healing spells to keep them going.  But as the sun started to disappear over the mountaintops, as they rested by a fire near the Runnyeye entrance, Marchant noticed an odd looking creature coming towards them.  It looked for all the world like a shambling pile of mud. "What is that?", he asked.<br><br>"A muddite," Barrik answered, drawing his weapons.  "An elder one, if I judge correctly.  Be careful.  They don't look like much, but they hit hard... very hard."<br><br>Marchant quickly learned how hard when the muddite hammered him with a powerful fist.  He staggered back a step as he returned the blow.  Barrik joined the battle, slashing the thing's shoulder with his granite tomahawk.  Amazingly, the wound seemed to close somewhat, though the creature grunted with pain.  It turned on Barrik and swung an arm in his direction, flinging mud in the ranger's face, blinding him.  As Barrik struggled to clear the mud from his eyes, the muddite turned back to Marchant, parrying his sword blow.<br><br>"Argggh!", Barrik yelled.  "My eyes!"  He struggled to quickly clear them as his partner fought with the muddite.  As his vision began to clear, he felt a cold stab of dread.  Behind Marchant, blocking the way to the passage was a huge minotaur.  He recognized it as one of the ones they has seen deep in a chasm earlier in the day.  "Chasm minotaur behind you!", he bellowed.  As he turned to block its path to his new friend, a second one slammed him sideways.  "Two of them!", he called.<br><br>With one final crushing blow, Marchant felled the muddite, and turned to the minotaur attacking him; deftly parrying it's first swing.  Though getting hammered by his own foe, Barrik aided his already-wounded partner, and they both flailed away, trying to kill one of the beasts quickly.  Near to collapse, Marchant landed a killing slash to the throat.  <br><br>Barrik quickly turned and landed a crushing kick to what passed for the remaining minotaur's knee, forcing it to briefly lose its balance.  Marchant, heedless of his own wounds, began healing the battered and bloody ranger.  However, his heals could not hope to keep up with the savage beating Barrik was receiving from his horned adversary.  All his mana finally exhausted, Marchant watched with horror as Barrik dropped to one knee from a devastating strike.<br><br>As Barrik lifted the sword gifted to him from Morin Shadowbane in what he knew was a last act of defiance, he saw the minotaur howl in triumph.  His vision started to turn gray, and he knew his life, and most likely the life of his new friend was about to end.  Suddenly, a rush of warmth and energy flowed through his body.  He felt every cut, every bruise, every fracture suddenly heal itself in an instant as the Holy Warrior of Mithaniel Marr laid his hands upon his shoulders and called for his god to aid him.<br><br>The giant minotaur fell back in surprise as his all-but-dead opponent suddenly turned and hit him in the solar plexus with a powerful side kick.  Marchant fell back against the rock wall of the gorge, all his strength spent, as Barrik, his full vitality returned, hit the misshapen beast with an incredible flurry of attacks.<br><br>Though it gave as good as it got, the minotaur was already badly wounded, and the Legionnaire pressed his advantage.  Even still, the great monster's fists and horns managed to take a heavy toll on him, and his newfound vigor began to wane.  As it swung a mighty fist at Barrik's head, a bright flash came from Barrik's axe, and a magical shield absorbed the impact.  When it looked at its hand in stunned surprise, the exhausted ranger drove Morin's sword deep into its heart.  With a final strangled cry, it fell to the ground in defeat.<br><br>Dropping to his knees, Barrik offered silent thanks to both Karana and Mithaniel Marr for their providence.  When he finished, he heard Marchant moving in front of him.<br><br>"Keep still," the paladin said quietly.  "Let me bind those wounds.  I have no mana left for healing, and we want to make the best of what you have."  Darkness descended completely as they tended to their wounds.  After the bandaging and healing was completed, they two exhausted half-elves made their way back to their camp.<br><br>Dawn broke too quickly, but sleep and spells had returned the two adventurers to full fighting trim.  Preparing to head off through the Runnyeye citadel towards Rivervale, Marchant asked Barrik, "Are you sure you don't want me to stay until your friend arrives?"<br><br>Barrik shook his head in the negative as he clasped the young paladin's hand. "No, that's all right.  He'll be here.  Fare well, my new friend.  May the Stormkeeper be between you and harm, in all the empty places you must walk."<br><br>Marchant saluted Barrik crisply.  "And may Mithaniel Marr's blessings be with you," he responded.  With that, he turned and walked down the tunnel.  <br><br>Barrik turned and faced the rising sun, and remembered his graying sight of the day before.  "They already have been, my friend.  They already have been."<br><br></p>&nbsp;<br><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>Arjaizen Izrhume<br>40th Circle Wizard of Erudin<br>Fallen Wolves</td></tr>
